<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID -- NATO has decided to invite the Czech Republic,
Hungary and Poland to join the alliance, NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solona announced Tuesday at the end of the first day
meeting of a two-day summit in Madrid, Spain. But a row remained
over the admission of Romania and Slovenia in the first wave, with
France and other eight nations backing the two countries' early
admission and the United States heading an opposition to it.
</P>
<P>
MADRID -- NATO leaders reaffirmed Tuesday that the NATO-led
Stabilization Force (SFOR) will remain in Bosnia and Herzegovina
till next June.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France said Tuesday that it favors an international
mobilization to pressure the conflicting sides of Cambodia to
resume dialogue over the present crisis in their country.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri Tuesday had
a government reshuffle and the new ministers, including four new
comers, were sworn in at the presidency headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Key cabinet members -- Defense Minister Mohammed Hussein
Tantawi, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Interior Minister Hassan
el-Alfy -- remain in their jobs. Ganzouri said the shake-up, the
first since he took office in January 1996, aimed at improving
efficiency of their work.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Cambodia's First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh
Tuesday called on the international community to condemn the "coup
d'etat" staged by Hun Sen, the country's second prime minister.
</P>
<P>
During a press conference in Paris today, Ranariddh called on
the international community, the United Nations, the signing
countries of the 1991 Paris peace agreements on Cambodia, the
European Union and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) "never to recognize a regime resulting from a coup d'etat."
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 22 people were killed and 46 others
injured in a powerful bomb blast in a speeding passenger train in
India's Punjab state Tuesday, Press Trust of India reported. The
reported casualties included six women and four children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
