<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Criticizes Western Countries for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Minister of Petroleum
and Mineral Resources Ali Al-Naimi today criticized some western
countries for imposing taxes on crude oil and warned that the
carbon tax would only harm its advocates.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the official Saudi Press Agency that such a
tax would also destabilize the international oil market, which he
hoped would remain a free commercial market.
</P>
<P>
His criticism is primarily directed against European countries
where taxes on oil, mainly gasoline, have been rising steadily
as a means to discourage the use of fossil fuels in favor of
more environment-friendly energy sources such as natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world top oil producer and exporter, and
other oil producing countries including other Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states, have been complaining bitterly about high
European taxes on oil which range from between 50 to 70 percent
of oil's original value.
</P>
<P>
They complained that these oil importing countries are making
more money from taxing oil than the exporters do from producing
it.
</P>
<P>
These oil-producing countries considers this tax as a
"single-minded approach" from the side of consumer states with no
observation of the interests of producing states and their
dependency on oil to promote their economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
