<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Funds on Human Development Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Managing Director of Consumer
Council of Zimbabwe Muchaneta Nyambuya today said it should be
possible to get rid of extreme poverty both nationally and
internationally over the next 20 years if the will is there.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a seminar on ''20/20 Initiative -- a New
Budget Concept'', Nyambuya said this would be a better approach
to tackling poverty rather than to bring the numbers of the very
poor down to three to four percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
Decent levels of human development, he said, could be achieved
in Zimbabwe if the government allocated more funds to human
development.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
had appealed to governments to allocate an average 20 percent of
public spending to human development resources.
</P>
<P>
''On average, especially in low-income countries, many of
these being African, more than 20 percent would be needed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
''Donors can then be called upon to fill the gap by allocating
20 percent of their aid budgets to human development
priorities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The 20/20 initiative, he said, was a way to increase
efficiency in the allocation of available national resources and
donor funds.
</P>
<P>
Representative of the World Bank Ebrahim Jassat told the
seminar, ''human resource development and poverty reduction are
fundamental to long-term sustainable growth.''
</P>
<P>
He said members of civil society, the government and the World
Bank would be meeting on July 14 in Washington for the launch of
the structural adjustment initiative.
</P>
<P>
''Zimbabwe was chosen as one of the case examples where civil
society and the state came together to review the positive and
negative aspects of the economic structural adjustment
programs,'' said Jassat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
