<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland Invited to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 8 (Xinhua) -- NATO has decided to invite the Czech
Republic, Hungary and Poland to join the alliance, NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solona said here today at the end of the
first day meeting of a two-day summit in Madrid, Spain.
</P>
<P>
As for other candidates, especially Romania and Slovenia,
Solana said: "We reaffirm that NATO remains open to new members
under Article 10 of the North Atlantic Treaty."
</P>
<P>
"No European democratic country whose admission would fulfil
the objectives of the Treaty will be excluded from consideration,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The initial row over whether to admit Romania and Slovenia
along in the first wave ended with a concession by France and
other eight nations to the United States' demand that the two
should wait until the next wave.
</P>
<P>
The invitation to the three former Warsaw Pact countries to
join NATO marks the official implementation of NATO's eastward
expansion plan, which came into being three and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to NATO's initial arrangements, the Czech Republic,
Hungary and Poland will respectively begin three-month
negotiations on their accession to NATO in September. If the talks
go smoothly, a protocol would be signed in December and the 16
NATO members will begin their ratification process early next year.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland are expected to become
NATO's new members in April 1999 if nothing goes wrong, when NATO,
the only military alliance existing after the end of the Cold War,
marks the 50th anniversary of the signing of the Treaty of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
NATO's current members are Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France,
Germany, Greece, Iceland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Norway, Portugal, Spain, Turkey, the United Kingdom, and the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
