<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Intelligence: Hamas Not Planning Massive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Army intelligence head
Moshe Yaalon today painted a relative positive picture of
Israel's security situation, saying the militant Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) is not planning massive terror
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Yaalon gave his assessment to the Knesset (Parliament)
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee. He noted that Hamas was
playing a passive role in the Palestinian territories and
refraining from taking part in the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) policy of controlled violence in Hebron and other places.
</P>
<P>
He said Hamas was gaining strength in the territories by
attacking PNA leader Yasser Arafat's policies for failing to
deliver peace dividends to the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Yaalon listed two reasons for Hamas' reluctance to launch
terror attacks against Israel at this stage: Firstly, the PNA is
cracking down on organized terrorism; secondly, Hamas is blamed
for the economic hardship in the territories caused by Israeli
closure as a result of the terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that another anti-Israeli militant organization
the Islamic Jihad was planning terror attacks at any time.
</P>
<P>
While commenting the PNA's efforts to crack down on organized
terrorism, Yaalon said Arafat was interested in keeping the
Palestinians on the international agenda by waging limited
violence in Hebron and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian police refused to restrain the rioters in Hebron,
and the situation would not change before Israel halted the
expansion of settlements and confiscation of Palestinian land,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the continued deadlock in the peace process to
the total lack of confidence between Israel and the PNA. However,
he disclosed that there was not total stalemate in the security
area as the two sides have been in quiet contacts over security
cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Yaalon added that Arafat had sought to contact Israel over
the building of the Dahaniya Airport in Gaza in order to rebuild
confidence between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu today
once again blasted the PNA for stalling the peace process and
violating the peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with a German television, Netanyahu
said that, despite the clashes in Hebron these days, the Israelis
today felt more secure than they did one year ago before he came
to power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
