<HEADLINE> Discussions on China's Reunification Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A discussion on China's
reunification was held here today between the Liaison Committee
for Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao Compatriots and Overseas Chinese
under the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) and a delegation from the US
Committee of One Hundred.
</P>
<P>
The US Committee of One Hundred, established in New York in
1991, consists of outstanding Chinese Americans from all walks of
life.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is here on a visit at the invitation of the
CPPCC National Committee
</P>
<P>
During the discussion, Chen Ziying, deputy director of the Hong
Kong and Macao Affairs Office under the State Council, briefed the
visitors on the negotiation process over Hong Kong issues and the
content of "one country, two systems." The concept of "one
country, two systems," which accords with the actual conditions
both in Hong Kong and China's inland area, would be unswervingly
carried out in Hong Kong, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In response to the questions raised by the US visitors, Tang
Shubei, deputy director of the Taiwan Affairs Office under the
State Council, said that China's sovereignty belongs to all the
Chinese including Taiwan compatriots. Although the two sides
across the Taiwan Straits have not reunified yet, the sovereignty
has never been split, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that China would continue to focus on its economic
construction, strictly abide by the terms set in the Sino-British
Joint Declaration and the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region and implement well the "one country, two
systems" policy in Hong Kong. "We will also make the Taiwan
compatriots understand this policy better," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tang pointed out that the reunification across the Taiwan
Straits needs time, but China's sovereignty can never be allowed
to be split under the pretext that the country is not reunified
yet.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Taiwan authorities would be
honest and the two sides across the straits conduct political
negotiations in a proper atmosphere and increase the links across
the straits to reach the goal of reunification eventually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
