<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Calls for Int'l Understanding of Cambodian Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen today pledged to do his best to restore public order and
asked the international community to understand his efforts.
</P>
<P>
In his third radio and television speech in three days, Hun Sen
said the international community should allow the Cambodian people
solve their own problems without external interference and
pressure.
</P>
<P>
Fightings with armed forces loyal to the country's First Prime
Minister Norodom Ranariddh had ended, he noted, adding that he
hoped everything would be back to normal as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said he had phoned Loy Sim Chheag, acting president of
the National Assembly (parliament) and secretary-general of the
FUNCINPEC Party, to discuss the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to convene a parliamentary session within a week
and work out new electoral and party laws within one month to pave
way for the general elections scheduled in May 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
The FUNCINPEC Party should nominate one person to take over
Ranariddh's position and parliamentarians who had not followed the
first prime minister will remain their posts, Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
Acting head of state Chea Sim had already sent letters to King
Norodom Sihanouk and Kofi Annan, secretary-general of the United
Nations, to brief them about the situation in Cambodia, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
