<HEADLINE> Kuwait Conglomerate Starts Billion-Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait state-owned National
Industries Company has started a new investment plan of one
billion U.S. dollars through the year 2005, chief executive
manager of the conglomerate Robert Kottritsch said today.
</P>
<P>
He said in an exclusive interview with Kuwait News Agency
that the 10-year executive strategy is aimed at expanding its
activities in the international market and competing for grand
specialized projects worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait National Industries Company is the second largest
industrial group in the Gulf region after the Saudi Arabian Basic
Industries Company. Its capital reached 1.21 billion U.S. dollars
at the end of 1996 with a net profit of 82.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far the company has investments in the Gulf Cooperation
Council states, Egypt and other Middle East countries and some
western and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Kottritsch said his company is vigorously seeking to put
into action its executive strategy in the globalization
campaign.
</P>
<P>
He said the company first planned to increase its investment in
 the Gulf region, mainly in iron and steel sector.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the company's plans in the Middle East region,
Kottritsch said it would try to expand its investments despite
difficulties in executing its plans due to lack of clear
investment and tax laws in some regional countries.
</P>
<P>
As for the company's global strategy, it would tap markets
in the southeastern Asian and the Pacific region, giving
priority to Singapore and Malaysia, while continuing to boost
its link with the western world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kottritsch said his company would diversify its activities
and overhauling the financial and administrative structures to
meet the requirements of its expanding strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
