<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabbah Urges Mutineer Soldiers to Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Ousted Sierra Leone leader Tejan
Kabbah today appeared on a radio, urging soldiers in the armed
forces "to report to the nearest ECOMOG base without arms and
declare their loyalty" to his deposed government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on a new fm radio station set up by Nigeria and based
near the international airport, 10 miles across the Sierra Leone
river, Kabbah said soldiers who report "will not be treated as
mutineers."
</P>
<P>
Kabbah also appealed to junta leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma
"to hand over power and spare themselves and the people of Sierra
Leone further pains and suffering."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria-led West African Peace-keeping Force known as ECOMOG
has threatened to use force to drive out Koroma and re-establish
Kabbah as the legitimate leader of the country.
</P>
<P>
"Hand over now and you will be forgiven by the people," he
said in a voice choked with emotion.
</P>
<P>
But Kabbah warned, "if you persists and caused force to be
used, let me assure you that no western or African country shall
offer you asylum and we shall not rest until you are brought to
justice."
</P>
<P>
Kabbah is in neighboring Guinea where he took refuge after the
May 25 coup. He said he had seen "babies and young people, old
men and women and the sick go into refugee camps."
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the broadcast, junta Secretary General, Colonel
Abdul Sesay accused Nigeria of "providing the logistics for the
setting up of the station."
</P>
<P>
"It is an infringement of our territorial sovereignty and this
must not be allowed," Sesay said.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the station as a pirate radio which will not
succeed.
</P>
<P>
Reaction to the station within the capital has been mixed. One
lawyer said he doubts "whether it could achieve anything as
people realize it will only paint the ousted government good."
</P>
<P>
Yet a university student welcomed the new station, saying, "it
will present an alternate view from the propaganda stuff dished
out by the government station." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
