<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar on Africa's Sustainable Development Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- An international workshop started
here today with an aim of promoting sustainable rural and
urban development in Africa through participatory approaches.
</P>
<P>
Rwabeire Baira, the director for Community Development in
Ugandan Ministry of Gender and Community Development, while
opening the one-week workshop, said it requires participatory
approaches to eliminate poverty which predominates African
countries.
</P>
<P>
Baira told community experts from 10 countries from within and
outside Africa to increase awareness among the people so that
they can manage their own resources.
</P>
<P>
He said poverty should not be taken as lack of money or
materials but should be considered as a result of lack of
confidence and awareness of hidden resources in the communities.
</P>
<P>
Baira asked the participants to promote community development
projects for use by workers throughout the continent.
</P>
<P>
Stan Burkey, senior advisor to Uganda Change Agnet Association
said sustainable development cannot be imposed on from outside
but should come from the actions of individuals.
</P>
<P>
Sustainable development is also an important issue in present
Africa, due to environmental degradation caused by deforestation
and over-grazing in most parts of Africa, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Open Embassies in Venezuela, Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will establish
resident diplomatic missions in Venezuela and Peru in the next
few months, the Department of Foreign Affairs announced today.
</P>
<P>
The decision took into account South Africa's emerging
priorities in it's foreign policy and political, economic and
other opportunities the countries had to offer, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
Some South African mining companies are already operating in
Venezuela and Peru, both having significant mining potential and
interested in joint ventures in this field with South Africa,
department sources said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa established diplomatic relations with Peru and
Venezuela in July and December in 1993 respectively. The two
Latin American countries have also opened embassies in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between South Africa and Venezuela stood at
41.96 million U.S. Dollars and that with Peru at 45.3 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently South Africa has resident diplomatic missions in six
Latin American countries. They are Argentina, Brazil, Chile,
Cuba, Mexico and Uruguay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Catholics Angry over Document Leakage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland Catholics were
getting angry today over a leaked official document which
suggested the government ignored their objections to a weekend
Protestant parade.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary, Mo
Mowlam, went into a new round of Northern Ireland peace talks in
the provincial capital Belfast, but overshadowed by Catholic fury
over the document, which concluded that allowing the parade along
Portadown's Catholic Garvaghy Road was "the least worst outcome."
</P>
<P>
However, the annual march that began on Sunday turned into the
worst riot seen in the divided province for years, with many
injuried and cars burned.
</P>
<P>
"Nationalists are very angry. Nationalists are thinking about
whether to talk to me or not so my use may be limited after my
failure in Garvaghy. I accept that," Mowlam said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary added that Catholic residents groups opposed to
Protestant weekend marches were not speaking to her after the
authorities allowed an Orange Order parade last Sunday over the
objections of Catholic residents who felt it was intimidation.
</P>
<P>
But she vowed to seek an agreement to avert further violence
when the Protestant Orange Order marches along Belfast's Lower
Ormeau Road on Saturday at the climax of the annual marching
season by pro-British Protestant organizations.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said Catholic anger continued till today. A
policeman patrolling disturbances on Portadown's Garvaghy Road was
shot and wounded as Catholics kept up a barrage of protest across
the province.
</P>
<P>
Irish Republican Army (IRA) guerrillas, which had been fighting
to end British rule of the province, was believed responsible for
his injuries and for a series of armed attacks on British troops
and police during overnight Catholic riots.
</P>
<P>
Since Saturday night there have been 776 attacks on the
security forces, 1,444 petrol bombings and 363 hijackings. A total
of 60 police and 49 civilians have been injured and police and
troops have fired 2,400 plastic bullets to quell riots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
