<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Islamic Bank of Development has ratified a
256-million-U.S.-dollar program to finance foreign development and
trade projects in member countries.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Jeddah-based bank said today that
the Council of Executive Directors approved the program during
their 171st session held in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Head of the bank Ahmad Mohammad was quoted as saying that the
council has already devoted 195 million U.S. dollars to finance
development projects in 10 member states, including 27 million
dollars to Iran, 26 million dollars to Kyrgyzstan and other Arab
and Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the council has specialized 33 million dollars to
fund foreign trade in Pakistan and Turkey and 25 million dollars
to Saudi Arabia's edible oil producing industry.
</P>
<P>
The bank also granted 2 million dollars to assist the
Palestinian people in addition to 840,000 dollars to fund
educational projects for Muslim minorities in non-Islamic
countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Union of Chambers and Commodity Exchange
(TOBB) Deputy Chairman Ali Osman Ulusoy said that Turkey was
benefiting from the so-called "suitcase" trade, which is conducted
through illegal channels, by at least 15 billion U.S. dollars each
year.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted Ulusoy as saying that
"suitcase" trade figures, which have not been registered to the
balance of payments, compensated Turkey's trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Ulusoy said that "suitcase trade has averaged 15 billion dollars
for the last five years, thus means 75 billions dollars in five
years. That amount of surplus helped our economy to survive."
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A fierce price war resulted in a loss of 750,000
Jordanian dinars (about 1 million U.S. dollars) to Jordan's major
tourist transport companies in the first half of the year,
according to the general manager of the Jordanian Investment and
Tourism Transport Company (Alfa), Isam Aridah.
</P>
<P>
Giving an example, Aridah said that a one-way journey from the
capital city of Amman to Petra, one of Jordan's historical sites,
is 500-kilometer long and cost 311 dinars (about 439 dollars), but
due to competition and abundance of buses, companies charge as low
as 150 dinars (about 212 dollars) which means a 161 dinars (about
227 dollars) loss per journey.
</P>
<P>
The price is the lowest in the Arab world, the general manager
said.
</P>
<P>
The major tourist transport companies will go bankrupt within
five years if they do not come together to agree on a pricing
formula in cooperation and coordination with the ministry of
tourism, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Aridah said a meeting will be held this week among
all the parties concerned to discuss a mechanism to stop the
financial bleeding of the tourist transport companies.
</P>
<P>
There are now altogether 240 tourism buses operating in the
kingdom, but the operational rate is no more than 50 percent on
average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Threatens to Block Spain's Full Entry into NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
threatened to block Spain's full integration into NATO's command
structure unless British military aircraft are allowed to make
full use of the airport on the contested British colony of
Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview early today, British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook put forward conditions for Spain to become a
full NATO member, saying "our case is that if Spain wishes to come
fully into the (NATO) Alliance and into the integrated command
structure, then it must behave as an ally when we want our
military aircraft to go in and out of Gibraltar."
</P>
<P>
Cook noted that the Spanish government was restricting the
access of British military aircraft to the airport on Gibraltar, a
rocky peninsula at the southern tip of Spain that dominates the
western entrance to the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
"Spain, at the moment, makes that very difficult because it
does not provide proper air space for our military planes, or
indeed our civilian planes, to take off there," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Gibraltar was ruled by Spain in the mid-15th century and merged
into Spanish territory in 1501. In 1704 Austria captured
Gilbraltar with the joining of Britain and the Netherlands. Under
the Treaty of Utrecht in 1713, Gibraltar formally became a British
colony, but Spain has claimed it ever since, generating regular
tensions with Britain.
</P>
<P>
Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar expressed his hope on
Monday that Spain would join NATO's military command later this
year, but he admitted there would be some hurdles to be overcome
first.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government has made it clear that Spain would
insist on a sub-regional Iberian command that would encompass all
its territory, including the disputed Gibratal.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the Spanish initiative, Cook said: "We have never
said, never recognized and do not recognize any probability of any
Spanish sub-regional command having any direct command over
Gibraltar. That's not on the cards."
</P>
<P>
When asked whether London would block Spain's integration into
NATO's command structure without a deal over Gibraltar, Cook said:
"Yes, we can and yes, we will, unless there's an agreement."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
