<HEADLINE> Short Calls for Business Partnership on Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Clare Short, Britain's International
Development Secretary, today called for a partnership of business
leaders to discuss ways of tackling world poverty and urged
business to give strong backing to the growing ethical movement.
</P>
<P>
"Business must be a partner with government and others in the
great development challenge", the secretary told an audience at
the Institute of Directors.
</P>
<P>
In a key speech where she set out Britain's new broader
approach to international development, she stressed the central
role the private sector played in eradicating poverty.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary also warned business against complacency,
particularly in the face of growing public concern over human
rights.
</P>
<P>
Short said: "Consumers are increasinly using their power.
Two-thirds of people now say they consider a company's ethical
stance when purchasing. Clearly business cannot afford to ignore
this. Ethical business makes good business sense."
</P>
<P>
The Secretary called on business to forge a "new partnership"
with government to take up the objective of halving world poverty
by 2015 and help small and medium scale enterprises to access
developing country markets.
</P>
<P>
Short also called on them to release finance for microfinance
schemes for very small businesses and develop regional
partnerships betweek UK regions and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary said that international development was not just
a "business for soft hearts", "it requires also the hardest of
heads".
</P>
<P>
It was time, said the Secrtary, to recognise the importance of
the private sector in eliminating world poverty, and to help
harness the power of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
It was true that private investment did account for vast
amounts of development assistance to the developing world, but
that, she maintained, was no cause for complacency.
</P>
<P>
"My hope is that we can increasingly work together towards a
shared sense of purpose in eliminating poverty from the globe,"
the Secretary concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
