<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. to Meet to Discuss Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the U.S. government
and the European Commission will meet here tomorrow to discuss the
future of electronic commerce, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The talks will reportedly focus on intellectual property,
security of transactions, electronic payment systems, data
protection, taxation and tariffs, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will give the team of the European Union's
executive body, chaired by Hans Beseler, director-general for
trade policy, the chance to explain its detailed initiative on
electronic commerce, launched last April.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. team will be led by Ira Magaziner, senior advisor to
U.S. President Bill Clinton and architect of the U.S. report on
electronic commerce presented by Clinton last week.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Jacques Santer, president of the European
Commission, agreed at their EU-U.S. summit, held in May in the
Netherlands, to treat electronic commerce as a top priority over
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be the first occasion for both sides to
exchange views and explore common grounds on future work on
electronic commerce. 
</P>
