<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Approves Measures Against Deputies of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian parliament,
House of People's Representatives, has approved measures to be
taken against deputies when they lose public credibility, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the measures, a constituency can recall its deputy if
15,000 voters endorse the request or if the majority of members
of the District Council vote to recall the deputy, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
A deputy can be described to have misconducted when he or she
fabricates information, lies, or presents unverified issues in
front of the house, it added.
</P>
<P>
The regulation provides for the house to take actions against
any deputy who have been found to have misconducted, based on the
suggestions of a house conduct committee, which will also have
the responsibility of probing into alleged misconducts.
</P>
<P>
The 547-member House of People's Representatives was formed in
August 1995 after national elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
