<HEADLINE> Israel Unveils Advanced Armored Fire-Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel has developed an advanced
armored fire-control system which allows tanks to shoot attack
helicopters out of the sky, according to a report of the state-run
Israel Television this evening.
</P>
<P>
The system, called the Baz, enables armored vehicles to shoot
in all conditions at moving targets on land and in the air. The
Baz was developed by El-Op Electro Optics industries and Elbit
Systems Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The project was led by Yisrael Tal, who in the 1970s initiated
the development of the Merkava tank and is now a senior official
in the Defense Ministry. The Israel Defense Forces (IDF) Armored
Corps, Tank Development Authority, and Ammunition Corps, also were
involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
The Baz is meant to be installed in the Merkava Mark-3 tank and
industry executives said it will significantly improve the tank's
performance.
</P>
<P>
"There are many benefits of this system compared to the fire
control systems of the previous generation," said Avi Azrad,
deputy director-general of El-Op, "among them the ability to carry
out battle missions during the day, night, in difficult weather
conditions, the ability to fire at moving targets such as tanks,
and those flying at altitudes such as attack helicopters."
</P>
<P>
The system received Israel Prize for Defense at the
Presidential Residence in Jerusalem Monday. "This is a unique
system, the fruit of original and advanced ideas," said Ya'acov
Hazan, one of the developers of the Baz at El-Op.
</P>
<P>
"Integrated with other Merkava tanks, the Baz places the
Merkava in the first line of the top tanks in the world,"
said Hazan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
