<HEADLINE> EC Approves Emergency Medical Aid for Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, has approved a package of
emergency medical aid worth 700,000 ECUs (some 910,000 U.S.
dollars) for Bulgaria, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The aid, managed by the European Community Humanitarian Office
(ECHO), will enable European non-governmental organizations to
supply and distribute medicines and medical supplies over the next
six months.
</P>
<P>
The grant will enable Deutsche Artzgemeinschaft fur
medizinische zusammenarbeit of Germany and Medecins sans
Frontieres of Switzerland to distribute supplies to selected
centers in Bulgaria over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria has had a turbulent transition since the collapse of
one-party rule in 1989. Medicines and medical supplies are among
the country's most urgent needs, for both hospitals and
government-run institutions such as homes for the elderly and
children.
</P>
<P>
Previous ECHO funding for humanitarian aid in Bulgaria
reportedly came to a total of 1.1 million ECUs (about 1.4 million
dollars). 
</P>
