<HEADLINE> Britain to Back U.S. Plan to Restrict NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
will line up with U.S. President Bill Clinton in demanding that
NATO's planned expansion should be limited to only three
countries, according to British government sources.
</P>
<P>
Blair is intending to take a robust line against France and
other NATO members which are pushing for five countries to join in
the first wave of NATO enlargement, Downing Street sources were
quoted as saying on the eve of the NATO Summit opening today in
Madrid, Spain.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that Blair will veto any attempt to include
Romania and Slovenia along with the preferred front-runners,
Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister is also to tell NATO leaders at the Madrid
summit that adding three more nations to the NATO alliance is a
"bold step", insisting on the American and British position on
"only three" must prevail.
</P>
<P>
The only concession Britain is prepared to make will be to go
along with the French commitment in the summit communique relating
to the next phase of the enlargement program, provided that no
countries are specifically named for the second wave, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair is unlikely to propose any countries for NATO
membership except Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary, they
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
