<HEADLINE> Cyprus Defends its Record on Fight Against Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has defended its record on
the fight against money laundering, saying strict Central Bank
supervision ensured that dirty money was consistently turned
away from the island.
</P>
<P>
Governor of Central Bank Afxentis Afxentiou announced at an
international conference on money laundering, which opened Monday
here, that "in the international fight against money laundering,
I am proud to say that Cyprus can be a model for many countries
of the world."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has signed both international conventions on money
laundering, namely U.N. Vienna Convention of 1988 and the Council
of Europe Convention of 1990, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus "has in place a very modern money laundering
legislation, extremely tight regulations and a vigorous policy
against money laundering," he told the conference.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Philippou, the central bank's chief senior manager,
who outlined the measures Cyprus is taking to fight international
financial crimes, said that Cyprus set up a special unit in
December 1996 to investigate cases of suspected money laundering.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, the Central Bank introduced a monthly reporting
system of large cash deposits in excess of 10,000 U.S. dollars
and unusual transfers routed through Cyprus, Philippou said.
</P>
<P>
Both statements by Afxentiou and Philippou, which are
available today, were designed to counter allegations in Western
media and by the U.S. State Department that Cyprus was not doing
enough to counter money laundering.
</P>
<P>
"All the indications available so far point to the fact that
Cyprus has not yet experienced a money laundering problem," said
Philippou.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is examining issues such as the
impact of organized crimes on national and international financial
systems, and suggestions for developing a response to
international organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
Afxentiou has put at 500 billion to 1 trillion U.S. dollars
the amount of money laundered every year across the world, of
which, he said, 70 percent is drug-related. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
