<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Peaceful solution to Cambodian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General kofi
Annan today urged the rival parties in Cambodia to negotiate a
peaceful solution to the recent crisis in the country, said a
statement by the spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is gravely concerned about the recent
crisis in Cambodia. He deeply regrets the loss of life that has
ensued, including that of the daughter of the UN Security Unit
Radio Operator. he was dismayed to learn today of the death in
custody of Hor Sok, co-Secretary of State for the Interior
Ministry," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"He called on both first Prime Minister Ranariddh and Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen to resolve the current political crisis
through negotiations, in accordance with the Paris Agreements and
the Cambodian Constitution," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the earlier commitment of the coalition government to
hold national elections in May next year, Annan said in the
statement the United Nations stood ready to coordinate
international observers for those elections.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed in the strongest manner the vital importance
of making every efforts to ensure that these elections, the first
to be held by the Cambodians themselves since the departure of the
United Nations peace-keeping force in 1993. would be free and
fair.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's coalition government, formed in 1993, collapsed into
violence on Saturday as forces loyal to the country's rival prime
ministers went to war in capital of Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
At least 58 people were killed and as many as 200 other,
mostly civilians, were wounded in the three days of violence.
</P>
