<HEADLINE> Security Situation Improves Greatly in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- With the July 19 general election
drawing near, it is possible to traverse the entire length and
breadth of Liberia without any fear of attack or molestation, the
News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported today.
</P>
<P>
A NAN correspondent who entered into Liberia through a village
on the border with Cote d'Ivoire said people now moved freely
both day and night.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the tremendous efforts by the west African
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG to restore normalcy in the
country, the incidence of armed banditry and pervasive
lawlessness has ceased everywhere, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The more than 400-km journey from Nimba county at the border,
where former warlord Charles Taylor launched his anti-government
rebellion thus igniting the civil war seven years ago, showed the
ECOMOG has full and firm control.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, ECOMOG checkpoints are a regular
feature along the entire route that cuts through thickly wooded
forests of lush-green vegetation and leads to the capital
Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
With the presence of the ECOMOG, some drivers and passengers
who regularly ply the road said the fear of attack has for long
become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
In Monrovia, night clubs at the city center are usually open
even on week days, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The multinational ECOMOG, after its success in disarming and
demobilizing the warring factions in the country earlier this
year, has promised to ensure security for Liberians.
</P>
<P>
It currently concentrates on keeping a safe environment
favorable for the country's first post-war elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
