<HEADLINE> Nigerian Textile Makers Fight Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Textile Manufacturers
Association (NTMA) has called on the federal government to
disallow foreign textile fabrics destined for neighboring west
African countries to be shipped through Nigerian ports.
</P>
<P>
Such fabrics were never taken out of the country and the
practice should thus be stopped, said NTMA President Walid
Jibrin, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
"Evidence has shown that such fabrics do not leave Nigeria and
in the absence of any mechanism to ensure that they get to their
countries of destination, we consider it in the national interest
that their transhipment should be stopped," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has made a decision recently that
escorts would accompany such goods to their destinations to
ensure that they are not dumped in the local market.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that it would stem the spate of dumping," the NTMA
president said, adding that the computerization of import duty
assessment by the department of customs and excise would stem
sharp practices of some importers of finished textiles.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, which boasts several large textile companies mainly
set up by businessmen from Hong Kong, has been textile production
and export base in west Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
