<HEADLINE> Cameroun to Tighten Measures to Curb Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Cameroun is going to take tighter
measures to curb illegal drug traffic and production, an official
from the National Assembly of Cameroun told Xinhua here today.
</P>
<P>
The official revealed that the Educational, Information and
Social Affairs Committee of the National Assembly started meeting
this afternoon to examine a new draft bill on drug control.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill was submitted to the assembly by Cameroun's
Ministry of Public Health, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to today's local newspaper "Cameroun Tribune",
Public Health Minister Charles Etoundi has to defend the bill in
the committee.
</P>
<P>
If the bill sails successfully through the committee and
eventually through the house, a new classification and rules
binding the production and sale of drugs and similar products
will be put in place, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed that Cameroun could not be left behind after
all other countries are grappling with the adverse effects of the
illegal production and traffic in drugs.
</P>
<P>
The central African sub-region and Cameroun in particular are
at a transit point between production areas of cocaine, canabis
and other drugs, and the European and North American markets.
</P>
<P>
These natural settings as well as the fact that few or no
legislative and judiciary measures exist to stamp out or
forestall the trade, have rendered the region a fertile area for
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The paper also noted that the absence of strict control
measures on the importation and the sale of these drugs on the
streets contributes largely to their abusive use in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
