<HEADLINE> US Ships on Alert for Possible Cambodian Evacuation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States has yet to
decide whether to evacuate its citizens from Cambodia, but three
ships carrying marines and helicopters are put on alert in Japan
in case an order comes forward for evacuation.
</P>
<P>
The commander-in-chief of the Pacific Command in Hawaii has
ordered the three ships, the Belleau, the Fort McHenry and the
Dubuque, on alert "for their potential use (for) evacuating
non-combatants and maybe third country nationals" from Cambodia,
Pentagon spokeswoman Lt. Com. Karen Jeffries said at a briefing
today.
</P>
<P>
The three ships, carrying several hundred marines and
helicopters, are now based at Sasebo in Japan. It would take them
four days to reach athe Cambodian coast if they receive the order
for evacuation.
</P>
<P>
But some other officials said the evacuation looks less likely
as the situation is actually easing after days of ferocious
fighting between rival factions in Phnom Penn, the capital of
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"The Pentagon is preparing for possible contingency if
something were to be necessary but so far the situation is
becoming more calm rather than less calm," they said.
</P>
<P>
"I think this is prudent preparation for a possible future need
but not something that's actually going on right now," they added.
</P>
<P>
The Phnom Penh fighting began Saturday after troops loyal to
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen moved against those supporting First
Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
