<HEADLINE> Britain Makes New Efforts to Ease EU's Beef Export Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- British Agricultural Minister Jack
Cunningham announced a new two-pronged effort today to ease the
European Union ban on Britain's beef exports.
</P>
<P>
Last month EU veterinary scientists rejected a British proposal
for a scheme allowing cattle from herds which never suffered from
the fatal disease to be certified safe for export.
</P>
<P>
The EU vets said they were concerned about the government's
ability to identify and trace all cattle at risk, but that if the
proposals were amended to address five weaknesses which they
identified, the scheme would prove acceptable.
</P>
<P>
Cunningham told parliament that the proposal was now being
revised to take account of the vets' criticisms.
</P>
<P>
"Eligibility for the scheme would be more restricted than
originally proposed, but it would still be open in principle to
producers in all parts of the United Kingdom," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that in parallel the government was
developing a new proposal for an export scheme based on the age of
cattle, details of which would be announced after exploratory
talks with the European Commission, the EU's executive arm.
</P>
<P>
"We have put our ideas to the Commission about both schemes,
and will press them with equal vigor," Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
Britain has been trying in vain to persuade the EU to allow it
to export beef since March of last year when the EU decided to ban
Britain's beef export for fear of getting "mad cow disease."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
