<HEADLINE> France Calls for End of Violence in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- France today called for a "return of
legal and constitutional order" to Cambodia and urged the two
conflicting parties to resume dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn the use of violence and we are very attentive to it
that fundamental liberties be respected," French Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Anita Limido said.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to the two parties for dialogue, and for a return to
the 1991 Paris accords (which renounced violence)," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the elections, scheduled for next May, should be held
as planned and it should be "just, equitable and organized under
incontestable conditions."
</P>
<P>
But Limido refrained from saying whether the French government
will continue to make contacts with Cambodia's First Prime
Minister, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who has fled to France after
heavy fighting broke out last Saturday between his troops and the
troops loyal to Second Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Limido said that so far no plan has been made to evacuate some
2,000 French expatriates living in Cambodia, most of them in or
near the capital Phnom Penh. There are also an unknown number of
French tourists in other parts of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh today flew to Washington and New York to seek support
from the United States and the United Nations. 
</P>
