<HEADLINE> China Sweeps 9 Golds, Breaks 4 World Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGZHOU, Southeast China, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China showed
their prowess by sweeping nine gold medals and breaking four world
records on the second day of the Asian weighlifting championships
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Wan Jianhui shattered the snatch world record with a
lift of 163 kilograms en route to taking all three gold medals for
the men's 70kg class.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Chinese bettered the previous world mark of
162.5 kilograms produced by compatriot Zhan Xugang in the Atlanta
Olympic Games and lifted 180 kilograms in clean-and-jerk to total
342.5.
</P>
<P>
Kim Myong-Nam of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and
Moldodosov of Kirghizstan finished second and third in the three
events.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Yang Xia won two gold medals from the women's 54kg
category as she set the new snatch world mark of 93.5 kilograms
and then totalled a world record weight of 207.5.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese Liu Xiuhua won the clean and jerk event as she
lifted a world record weight of 115.5 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Liu also won two silver medals from the snatch and total
events.
</P>
<P>
Ri Song-Hui of DPR Korea took all three bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 64kg class, Chinese Yang Chunkang walked away with
all three gold medals with a total weight of 302.5 kilograms
(137.5+165).
</P>
<P>
Hwang Eui-Youl of South Korea got all three silver medals by
totalling 295 kilograms (135+160).
</P>
<P>
Y. Irlamov of Kirghizstan won a bronze medal from the snatch
event with a lift of 122.5 kilograms. The other two bronzes went
to Liao Hsin-Chou of Chinese Taipei, who totalled 272.5 kilograms
(120+152.5). 
</P>
