<HEADLINE> Canada's Ontario Hydro Dumps Metal into Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Ontario Hydro has admitted
dumping thousands of tons of metal emissions into the Great
Lakes, media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The crown corporation has shown " a lack of respect for the
environment", President Allan Kupcis admitted following the
release of a report on metal emissions at power plants on the
Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
The report said the corporation had released 1,813 tons of
six common metals -- copper, zinc, arsenic, iron, lead and tin --
from the brass condensers at six power stations.
</P>
<P>
Of this amount, more than two-thirds has been released from the
Pickering nuclear station since it went into operation in 1971.
</P>
<P>
The report, commissioned in late May, was conducted by two
senior Hydro staffers, a medical officer and a university
professor.
</P>
<P>
It concludes that there does not appear to be a strong
environmental ethic within the nuclear-power side of the business.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it is quick to point out that testing has shown there is
evidence to suggest risk to human health.
</P>
<P>
Kupcis called the situation "disappointing and unacceptable".
He promised that his corporation will immediately fix the main
problem in its nuclear and fossil-fuel-powered generating
stations.
</P>
<P>
It will involve replacing old and inadequate copper pipes used
to carry cooling water, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Canadians Use Debit Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- More and more Canadians use debit
cards in transactions, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
A survey of more than 2,000 adults found that debit card was
second only to cash as the preferred means of payment in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent of those surveyed said they preferred to pay by
cash. 22 percent said they preferred to pay by debit card, up from
only 9 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The credit card was the preferred means of payment by 17
percent of those surveyed. Seven percent preferred to pay by
check, down from 12 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
With a credit card, the user gets up to 7 weeks of free credit.
Yet, the user ends up paying hefty interest if he or she fails to
pay the balance on time.
</P>
<P>
With a debit card, the amount of the purchase is withdrawn at
once, electronically, from the card user's bank account.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Canadians made 676 million purchases with debit
card. This year, close to one billion purchases with debit card
are expected.
</P>
<P>
The number of purchases using credit cards is expected to be
about the same in Canada, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
