<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Agrees with New U.N. Mission on Massacre in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- France today expressed agreement with
the decision by the United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to
send a new mission to investigate alleged massacre of Hutu
refugees by the troops of Laurent-Desire Kabila in Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRCongo).
</P>
<P>
But France warned that the new mission must have the same
mandate of a previously planned mission by the U.N. Human Rights
Commission which was rejected by Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Annan Tuesday yielded to the demand by Kabila to replace the
previous investigation team with a new team of experts, because of
the presence within it of a Chilean lawyer, Roberto Garreton, who
said he had enough evidence of massacres to warrant a full
investigation.
</P>
<P>
"France is driven by a double concern: on the one hand, the
mission of inquiry should take place as quickly as possible to
answer the preoccupations of the international community, " said a
French Foreign Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman warned that the United Nations should not
"create a grave precedent by giving up a mission given mandate by
the Human Rights Commission, at the request of the accused state,
or to change its mandate."
</P>
<P>
He also deplored what he described as "the attitude of refusal
by Mr. Kabila" toward the U.N. investigation into alleged
massacres of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
