<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Be Better Tomorrow: Chief Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
 the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), today said
with confidence that Hong Kong will become better in the future.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Ninth Assembly of the Lutheran World Federation
held here, Tung said that Hong Kong entered a new era just over a
week ago. "On July 1, after 156 years of separation, Hong Kong
celebrated joyfully its reunification with China."
</P>
<P>
"The historic event filled Hong Kong people with pride and
confidence," "because for the first time in our history, Hong Kong
 people took on the solemn responsibility of managing our own
affairs" and "because we know that under the 'one country, two
systems' concept, Hong Kong will be even better tomorrow," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive stressed that the smooth and peaceful
handover of Hong Kong represents a new testament to the vision and
 ingenuity of the "one country, two systems" concept.
</P>
<P>
Under the Basic Law, which provides the constitutional
framework for the HKSAR, the central government of the People's
Republic of China has granted Hong Kong a high-degree of autonomy
and has guaranteed the continuation of its previous systems and
way of life for many years to come, he went on to say.
</P>
<P>
"The HKSAR government will preserve the existing freedoms and
lifestyle, and ensure that the people of Hong Kong will continue
to enjoy the freedoms of speech, assembly, association, press and
other freedoms," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted, "one of the important freedoms that my
government will preserve is, of course, the freedom of religion."
</P>
<P>
Article 141 of the Basic Law clearly stipulates that the HKSAR
government shall not restrict the freedom of religious belief,
interfere in the internal affairs of religious organizations or
restrict religious activities which do not contravene the laws of
Hong Kong, Tung added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
