<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Provisional Legislature Passes Immigration Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Legislators of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) today pushed through an
immigration bill in all three readings.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration (Amendment) No 5 Bill was tabled to the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) for passage into law today
at the interim body's first sitting at the Legislative Council
Building in Central, Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
Under the Bill, a certificate of entitlement scheme is
introduced for children born, in the Chinese inland areas, to Hong
Kong permanent residents. These children are entitled to the right
of abode in Hong Kong, according to the Basic Law of the HKSAR,
but they must come in a legal and orderly way.
</P>
<P>
When entering Hong Kong, they are required to have one-way
permits -- the valid documents to migrate to Hong Kong issued by
concerned departments in the inland areas, plus a "certificate of
entitlement" issued by the Immigration Department of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Joint investigations on the status of applicants will be
conducted by the inland and Hong Kong authorities.
</P>
<P>
In moving the Bill to the interim legislature, Peter Lai, the
secretary for security, said that the scheme would ensure that an
estimated 66,000 inland-born children with the right of abode
would enter the SAR legally and in an orderly manner, and would
enjoy their entitled rights and welfare.
</P>
<P>
A bills committee under the PLC went through the legislation
clause-by-clause at a six-hour meeting Tuesday, after the Bill was
 endorsed by the Executive Council during its first post-handover
sitting early in the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
