<HEADLINE> Hang Seng To Open New Inland Area Branch After HK Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Hang Seng Bank has become the
first bank in Hong Kong to win permission from the People's Bank
of China to open a branch in Shanghai after Hong Kong's return to
its motherland on July 1, a press release said today.
</P>
<P>
In the press release circulated here, the bank announced that
it has been permitted to upgrade its representative office in
Shanghai to a branch, marking a significant strengthening of its
presence in the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai branch will be the second inland area branch to be
set up by the bank, following the opening of its Guangzhou branch
in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai has become the key financial center on the mainland,
given its strategic location and the vast investment opportunities
the city offers to foreign investors," said Chairman of the bank
Lee Quo-wei.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The bank will be located in Pudong, the flourishing
financial hub which is the Chinese government's pilot site for the
conduct of RMB (China's currency) operations by overseas banks."
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, major projects financed by the
bank in Shanghai include the construction of Yangpu Bridge, the
Shanghai container port, the reconstruction of old districts, the
development of residential and commercial property projects.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Pudong branch is expected to be opened before the
end of this year. It will have an initial working capital of
convertible foreign currencies equivalent to RMB 100 million and a
staff of about 30.
</P>
<P>
The bank's presence in the inland areas dates back to 1985,
when it opened its first inland area representative office in
Shenzhen, South China. Its Xiamen (a big city in South China) and
Shanghai representative offices were established in 1986 and 1991,
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
