<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Respects Poll Body's Decision on Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said today he respected the decision made by the Commission on
Elections (Comelec) to reject the petition seeking to alter the
constitution so that Ramos can run for a second term.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly press conference, Ramos said the Comelec has all
the prerogative in exercising its decision throwing the petition
of the People's Initiative for Reform, Modernization and Action
(Pirma), a pro-Ramos private group.
</P>
<P>
The poll body Tuesday voted unanimously to dismiss the PIRMA's
petition signed by about 5.6 million people, who support changes
to the country's 1987 constitution to lift term limits on all
elective government officials, including the president.
</P>
<P>
"The Comelec decision speaks for itself and the Comelec should
be given the due credit for exercising their prerogatives in that
manner," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Comelec made the decision based on the ruling
issued by the Supreme Court which permanently stops the Comelec
from entertaining any people's initiative to change the charter.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that it is now up to the PIRMA whether to seek a
review of the high tribunal's ruling or not.
</P>
<P>
The constitution, which was enacted in 1987 to prevent
dictatorship in the country, stipulates that the president can
only serve one single six-year term.
</P>
<P>
But the PIRMA, established by Ramos' supporters in late 1996,
said Ramos' term should be extended due to his contribution to
economic boom in the country.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has claimed on many occasions that he will step down
after his term of office expires in June 1998. But he also
clarified that the people has the legal right to propose
amendments to the constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
