<HEADLINE> ASEAN Deeply Concerned With Cambodian Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said today that the Philippines, together with other members of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), is deeply
concerned with the situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly press conference at the Presidential
Palace, President Ramos said that although there was a lull in the
fighting in Cambodia at present, its fundamental political
situation remained unsettled.
</P>
<P>
Ramos urged the co-prime ministers of Cambodia, Prince Norodom
Ranariddh and Hun Sen, to exert every effort to set aside their
differences and work together in the interests of the whole
nation's reconciliation, peace and progress.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility that Cambodia might be rejected by ASEAN,
Ramos called on all parties and people to stop making speculations
on this sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the seriousness and sensitivity of this matter, I
would suggest that we all await the results of the meeting (of
ASEAN foreign ministers) and until the foreign ministers shall
have submitted their views and recommendations to their respective
leaders," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers are expected to meet Thursday in
Kuala Lumpur to discuss the situation in Cambodia and its planned
entry to ASEAN this month.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. It plans to admit Burma, Cambodia
and Laos into the community this month. 
</P>
