<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Confident of Russia's Army Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin today expressed optimism about the reform of the
Russian Armed Forces, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a session of the commission for the military reform,
Chernomyrdin said the reform envisaged cutting defense
spending and minimizing losses before 1998.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the army reform cannot be carried out without
"taking into account the economy, without thorough and accurate
calculation, without putting into order the finances of the Army
and the Navy."
</P>
<P>
This economy drive should result in the changing of the
numerical strength of the Armed Forces and of the existing
armaments program, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the third session of the commission, will discuss
how to carry out President Boris Yeltsin's instructions on the
army reform among other topics.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin on Tuesday signed the decree "on measures for the
payment of wage arrears to workers of the budget-financed sector
and to servicemen" and other decrees.  
