<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Faces Risks, Challenges and Opportunities, Says Solana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is facing risks, challenges and opportunities
in the Euro-Atlantic region, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana
told a news briefing at the end of the two-day summit here.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's summit meeting of the newly-established
Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council (EAPC) was the first of its kind
between the heads of states and governments of NATO and its
Partnership for Peace (PfP) countries.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus today was on the risks, challenges and opportunities
for effective cooperative security in the Euro-Atlantic area,"
Solana said.
</P>
<P>
EAPC, set up in May 1997, replaced the North Atlantic
Cooperation Council established at the end of 1991. It provides
the overarching framework for political and security-related
consultations and for enhanced cooperation under PfP.
</P>
<P>
Solana told reporters that the participants talked about how
EAPC could most effectively serve the interest of its 44 member
countries and contribute to their security and stability.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting reinforced the conviction that the security
of all allied and partner countries was inseparably linked. "EAPC
will be of fundamental importance in developing NATO's
relationship with Partners," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
