<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Welcomes DPRK's Decision to Join Four-Way Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
today welcomed the decision of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) to join the four-party talks with South Korea, the
United States and China.
</P>
<P>
"It is inspiring that an agreement to open a preliminary
meeting to the four-party talks has been made," Kim told an
unification conference in downtown Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from South Korea, the DPRK, the United States and
China will meet in New York on August 5 to work out the details of
the four-way talks, such as the agenda, level of representation,
venue and date.
</P>
<P>
Kim said he hoped that the four-party talks will be opened as
soon as possible and that the meeting will enable his country and
the DPRK to begin sincere discussions on ways to establish
permanent peace on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"Ensuring solid peace of the peninsula is an urgent task not
only for the future of our people but also for the stability of
Northeast Asia as a whole," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
Kim said another important task is to reduce tension and
restore mutual confidence between his country and the DPRK by
promoting bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that trade between South Korea and the DPRK is steadily
growing. South Korea is expanding investments in its northern
neighbor, supporting the construction of nuclear reactors there
and providing civilian food aid, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, we plan to discuss ways to help the North (DPRK)
solve its food shortage problems fundamentally at the four-party
talks," said the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
