<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Moved To Suspend Seven Pre-handover Ordinances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A bill to suspend seven
pre-handover laws was tabled to the Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region for
the first and second readings here today.
</P>
<P>
At the Council's inaugural sitting in the Legislative Council
Building starting at 2:30 this afternoon, Anson Chan, the Chief
Secretary for Administration, moved that Legislative Provisions
(Suspension of Operation) Bill 1997 be read the second time.
</P>
<P>
The Bill aims to suspend seven Ordinances passed at the last
sitting of the pre-handover Legislative Council, Chan told the
legislators. The seven laws include five labor-related Ordinances,
Protection of the Harbor Ordinance and Hong Kong Bill of Rights
(Amendment) Ordinance 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chan said that most of these Ordinances have far reaching
implications for government policies and operations, but they have
not been fully considered before enactment.
</P>
<P>
"As they represent a major departure from government policies,
we consider it prudent to review each piece of legislation
carefully to assess the social, economic and political
implications," the chief secretary for administration told the
Council.
</P>
<P>
She urged the PLC members to proceed as quickly as possible
with the Bill in order to minimize the changes effected by the
seven Ordinances that have already come into force.
</P>
<P>
Chan appealed to the PLC members to resume the second reading
debate on the Bill at the Council's sitting next week and to pass
the Bill.
</P>
<P>
Three other Bills were also moved today for the first and
second readings, including Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
Passport Bill, Chinese Nationality (Miscellaneous Provisions) Bill
and United Nations Sanctions Bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
