<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Report on European Demographic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- There will be more people leaving
the workforce than entering it in the European Union (EU)
countries after the year 2010, a report adopted today by EU's
executive body, the European Commission, shows.
</P>
<P>
The demographic report, which covers the period from 1995 to
2015, focuses on three main areas -- the impact of demographic
change on the labor market, the regional dimension of aging, and
the demographic situation in the countries which have applied to
join the EU.
</P>
<P>
The significant decrease in birth rates from 1970 onwards has
resulted in fewer people joining the labor force since 1990, says
the report.
</P>
<P>
Over the period from 1995 to 2005, the active population in the
15 EU member states may moderately increase by some 6.9
million. In the decade beginning from 2005, a drop of 2.1 million
is expected, it says.
</P>
<P>
The report predicts that the countries which have applied to
join the EU will also experience a significant fall in the working
population after 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
