<HEADLINE> Tamil Rebels Hijacks a DPRK Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Navy was closely
monitoring a cargo ship of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK), which was abducted by a Tamil rebel suicide squad on
Tuesday afternoon, security sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that one of the 38 DPRK crew members on board
the ship of Morang Bong was killed by the rebels of Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), and any attack on the ship would
harm the unarmed 37 other crew members.
</P>
<P>
The International Red Cross has been approached by the ship
owners to secure the release of the vessel and the crew, according
to the sources.
</P>
<P>
So far, there has not been any report from the LTTE as to why
it abducted the vessel and crew or as to what their demands are,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The ship had been chartered by traders from Colombo to carry
essential goods to Point Pedro for civilians in the North of the
country.
</P>
<P>
It was returning from Point Pedro after unloading its cargo to
north of Mullaitivu, over 200 kilometers from Colombo, when the
LTTE rebels hijacked it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
