<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Growth Booming in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital of Beijing has
had a total of 74.41 billion yuan of GDP in the first half of this
year, a year-on-year increase of 11.2 percent, according to Tang
Long, director of the city's Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture increased by 3.2 percent, industrial production,
11.9 percent, while the service sector reported a growth of 11
percent, indicating sound economic development, Tang told a news
conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rapid industrial increase to state
enterprises, especially those that are technology-intensive in the
Zhongguancun High-Tech Industrial Development Zone, known as
China's Silicon Valley, which contributed 60 percent to the growth
produced by the state industrial sector in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets was kept at a low level, with
investment in real estate dropping 7.1 percent, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Exports were expected to collect 1.1 billion US dollars, an
increase of 1.4 percent, while imports totaled to 1.46 billion US
dollars, up 5.1 percent. The city used overseas investment 930
million US dollars, rising 11.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Residents' incomes grew steadily, with an average increase of
8.5 percent in workers' wages, and of two percent in farmers'
revenues in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Tang said, however, that this economic foundation still is not
good enough for sustained and steady development of Beijing's
economic performance, and an insufficient demand and irrational
economic structure remain the major problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
