<HEADLINE> Nairobi Varsity Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- the University of Nairobi was shut
down today as Opposition parties continue to call for more
actions to press for constitutional reforms before the coming
General Elections.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Francis Gichaga, Vice-Chancellor
of the university, said despite the appeal for calm in the
circular released on Tuesday, the situation on the main campus
had continued to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the closure was necessitated by the
violent actions taken by students since last weekend when
political unrest broke out in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this morning, students from the university took to the
streets to demonstrate following reports carried by Daily Nation
which said four fellow students had died of wounds in the Monday
clashes with police.
</P>
<P>
However, police spokesman Assistant Commissioner Peter
Kimanthi denied the report, saying that it was "pure falsehood".
</P>
<P>
He said only two students died in incidents which were
completely unrelated to the confrontations between riot police
and Opposition supporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that one student died yesterday at
Kenyatta Hospital. "We do not know what caused his death but we
are investigating," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Another student was knocked down by a hit-and-run lorry. It
was a road accident and we are also investigating the accident,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
When the students blocked the main road in the capital city of
Nairobi this morning at the height of the morning rush hour,
Kenyan police moved in to confront the rioting students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
