<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Bourse Nosedives on Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine stock market today
continued to nosedive on rising fears that the Central Bank will
have to further raise its interest rates to protect a possible
devaluation of the country's currency peso.
</P>
<P>
The 30-share Philippine composite index (Phisix), which began
to decline Monday due to fears over the volatility of the foreign
exchange market, surprisingly breached the 2,600 psychological
support level today.
</P>
<P>
The Phisix, the main index for the Philippine Stock Exchange,
plummeted by 109.46 points or 4 percent, the biggest drop in two
and a half years, to 2,589.2 points. The broader all shares index
also declined by 33.84 points to 845.25.
</P>
<P>
All subindices suffered decline, with the mining sector
incurring the biggest drop of 252.3 points to 3,680.42. The
previously-battered property sector also sank by 88.2 points.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 6.5 billion with a value of
2.23 billion pesos (85 million U.S. dollars). The decliners
continued to outnumber the advancers by 141 to 10, with 39 other
issues unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Phisix shed 54.49 points, or 1.98 percent, to
close 2,698.66.
</P>
<P>
The tumble in the local bourse in the past few days offset
almost all the grounds the market has regained since late May when
it began to recover from a long-time decline triggered by fears of
a Thai-style financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts here said the main reason for the recent tumble
in the local bourse was the rising fears that the peso could face
greater pressure to be depreciated and the Central Bank will be
forced to further hike its overnight borrowing rates.
</P>
<P>
The peso has been under great pressure to be devalued under
waves of speculative attacks during the past several months,
particularly after the Thai government decided to float baht early
this month.
</P>
<P>
After the floatation of baht in Thailand, speculators shift to
the peso. To fend the peso off a fresh wave of speculative attack
Monday, the Philippine Central Bank raised its overnight borrowing
rates, for the third time in one week, from 20 percent to a
two-year high of 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the pressure on the peso and the uncertainty in
the foreign exchange market are now spilling over into the stock
market and investors are scared by the continued jump in overnight
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
They said many investors flocked over to fixed income
securities like treasury bills rather than stocks because fixed
income securities are offering higher yields than these stocks.
</P>
<P>
The analysts expected the market to continue a downtrend in the
near future since foreign and big institutional investors remain
shy away from the local bourse and continue to wait and see the
situation in the local foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
But analysts also said despite today's drastic drop in the
Phisix, the fundamentals of the local bourse are still sound. Once
the Thai crisis is resolved and furor over the peso dies down,
investors will return to the stock market, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
