<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Not to Join NATO If Citizens Disagree, PM Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister Horn
Gyula announced today that his country will hold a referendum on
whether it will join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
If the majority of the citizens refuse to seek a membership of
NATO, Hungary may not join the international organization, Horn
said.
</P>
<P>
Horn's announcement came after the NATO leaders decided to
invite Hungary to join the Western military alliance in its first
wave of expansion. The invitation has been welcomed by all
political parties in the National Assembly, which hail it as a
diplomatic victory won by two terms of government over the past
seven years through " strenuous efforts."
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders meeting at a summit in Madrid on Tuesday moved
towards an historic agreement on admitting former Soviet bloc
enemies -- Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic, as members of
the alliance.
</P>
<P>
The United States is insisting NATO's first wave of enlargement
be limited to the three countries and rejecting a drive led by
France and Italy for Slovenia and Romania to be included.
</P>
<P>
France insists, however, Slovenia and Romania are crucial to
security on NATO's southeastern flank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
