<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forum for Economic Coop Set Up in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe today
launched a National Economic Consultative Forum (NECF) to provide
a framework for cooperation among private sector, the government
and the employees.
</P>
<P>
The forum, comprising 62 members from the private sector,
non-governmental organizations, academic institutions and civil
society, would be chaired by Industry and Commerce Minister
Nathan Shamuyarira with Mugabe as its patron.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said important issues to be resolved by the forum
should include formulation of strategies to mobilize resources
for investment and the indigenization of the economy.
</P>
<P>
''I would like to stress that the planned targets should be
aimed at those areas that are catalytical to overall economic
growth such as mobilization of financial resources for the medium
and long term investment, acceleration of commercialization and
privatization of state enterprises,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He mandated the forum to recommend strategies that could be
used to promote participation of the indigenous people in the
mainstream economy.
</P>
<P>
The private sector, Mugabe said, could use the forum to spell
out the assistance it required from the government to facilitate
that promotion.
</P>
<P>
On the participation of the labor force, Mugabe said the
challenge was to ensure that workers had ownership in the
production process through equity participation and other
facilitative mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The idea of the forum is based on the smart partnership
philosophy which is an ambitious step to economically empower
developing nations and ward off domination of rich nations
through accelerated growth and fostering relationships among
government, private sector and labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
