<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pumps 71 Million Tons of Onshore Crude in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China's onshore oil production is
maintaining strong growth momentum this year, and the country had
turned out 71.07 million tons of crude and 8.41 billion cu m of
gas by the end of this June.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official with the China National
Petroleum Corp (CNPC), the country's onshore daily output in the
first half year increased by 4,389 tons compared with the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Onshore crude production has two distinguishing characteristics:
</P>
<P>
The aging oilfields in east China maintain stable oil output
and have completed 50.37 percent of the State-set annual output
target, while the newly-developed oil fields in West China have
witnessed sharp rises in oil production, with average daily output
outpacing the figure of the same period of last year by 6,350 tons.
</P>
<P>
And by the end of this May, the oil fields of Daqing, Shengli,
Liaohe, Henan, Dagang and Xinjiang have applied the technologies
of polymer-propelling and injecting water into oil wells to
produce more oil.
</P>
<P>
The CNPC source noted that the new technologies had helped to
increase crude output by 1.08 million tons in the first half of
the year, and an increase of 2.6 million tons is expected for the
whole year.
</P>
<P>
Great headway has also been made in onshore oil and gas
exploration; a total geological oil reserve of 545 million tons is
expected to be verified by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local, Foreign Carmakers Compete Over S. Korean Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Both local and foreign carmakers are
shedding blood in fierce competition over the saturated market in
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
In the luxury sedan sector, South Korean auto makers challenge
imports with various sophisticated options while the latter
counters with reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai, the largest auto maker in South Korea, offers an
exclusive back-seat television, high quality stereo system,
back-seat airbag and navigation system as options for its Dynasty
and New Grandeur, while Kia, the third largest carmaker, puts up
back-seat massage and automatic light control headlight.
</P>
<P>
Sangyong Motor Company joined the competition by equipping its
new sedan, Chairman, with various Benz technologies and navigation
system.
</P>
<P>
Importers, on the other hand, are counteracting by slashing
prices.
</P>
<P>
U.S. carmaker Chrysler cut the price of its 3.5-liter version
to 36,076 U.S. dollars from 43,123 dollars while BMW offers its
523 and 323 models with prices lowered by 2,000 to 3,000
dollars. For the 1996 735 models, BMW slashed the price tag as
much as 11,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. company, Ford, also reduced the price of 3-liter
Taurus to 32,135 dollars from 38,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the medium sized vehicle sector, South Korean companies
introduced various bargain installment plans to consolidate their
positions.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo Motor's Company, the second largest carmaker in the
nation, introduced a sort of leasing installment system for the
first time among domestic carmakers on its main models Lanos,
Nubira and Leganza.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, consumers pay 60 percent of the price tag in
stallments on the condition that they return the used car in three
years.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo introduced the system despite major margin losses as a
strategy against the no-interest installment sales put forth by
its major domestic competitors Hyundai and Kia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
