<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Malaysian Supreme Head of State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that the frequent exchanges of visits between the leaders of
 China and Malaysia have given a constant impetus to the two
countries' relations.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the remark in a meeting here this afternoon
with visiting Malaysian Supreme Head of State Tunku Ja'afar.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that Ja'afar's current China visit would have a major
impact on the further development of Sino-Malaysian friendly and
cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
China and Malaysia have engaged in many cooperation projects,
and the economic and trade collaboration between the two countries
has witnessed substantive progress, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also share many common views and help each
other in international and regional affairs, Li continued, adding
that the Chinese government places major importance on
Sino-Malaysian relations, and a good relationship between the two
countries is not only in line with the fundamental interests of
the two peoples, but also helpful for the peace and stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's experience in developing agriculture and water
conservancy is worth drawing on, Li remarked.
</P>
<P>
Touching on Sino-ASEAN relations, Li voiced China's
congratulations on the 30th anniversary of the establishment of
the organization this year. He also expressed his thanks for the
efforts made by Malaysia in promoting Sino-ASEAN links over the
past few decades.
</P>
<P>
Ja'afar told Li that he had had a very "friendly and useful"
meeting with Chinese President Jiang Zemin. He said that he hoped
that his China tour would reinforce the friendly and cooperative
ties between his country and China in every field.
</P>
<P>
The supreme head of state expressed his congratulations on the
smooth return of Hong Kong to the motherland, and said that it
reflects the wisdom and farsightedness of the Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has close relations with Hong Kong and with whole
China, and the return of Hong Kong has provided even broader
prospects for cooperation between Malaysia and China, Ja'afar said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government is looking forward to Premier Li
Peng's visit, Ja'afar told Li, and the latter expressed his
thanks. 
</P>
