<HEADLINE> Kuwait, French Oil Companies Signs Technical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Oil Company (KOC), the
oil producing arm of the state-owned umbrella Petroleum
Corporation, and French Total Oil Company signed here today a
consultancy agreement for technical services in the fields of gas
and oil.
</P>
<P>
The three-and-half-year agreement was signed after several
months of talks, KOC's board chairman and managing director Khalid
Yusif Al-Fleij said.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the French company would supply
technical expertise and know-how to the KOC in developing oil
reservoirs in the Gulf oil rich state.
</P>
<P>
Al-Fleij said the deal would provide a good opportunity for
training Kuwaiti employees on modern techniques along with the
operational methods which have enabled Total to be one of
the successful oil companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said the deal would also allow the KOC to use the modern
technologies available at Total, which became the first French
company to sign a deal with the KOC concerning operations inside
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the deal stipulates that Total would
make available to KOC its technology, expertise and know-how
to help KOC select the most effective approach to develop
its oil reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement mainly involves the provision of
technical consultancy and advice for the neutral zone oil
field which straddles the border with Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The neutral zone produces about 240,000 barrels of oil per
day, which is shared by Kuwait and Saudi Arabia under a
boundary agreement which dates back to 1922.
</P>
<P>
The KOC currently has a sustainable production capacity of 2.4
million barrels of oil per day and plans to raise that to 3
million barrels per day by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait actually produces about 2 million barrels of oil
per day in line with the quota set by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The KOC has similar technical service accords with British
Petroleum and U.S. firm Chevron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
