<HEADLINE> Adventurers Reach ROK After Successful Sea Expedition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Korean expedition finished
a voyage by bamboo raft and arrived at Inchon Port in the Republic
of Korea (ROK) Tuesday afternoon, it was learned from Hangzhou
University today.
</P>
<P>
Four adventurers from the ROK and one Chinese spent 23 days on
the ten-m-long and five-m-wide raft made of 80 lengths of bamboo,
according to the Research Institute of ROK Studies of the
university, one of the sponsors of the expedition.
</P>
<P>
Their voyage across the East China Sea and the Yellow Sea
between the Chinese mainland and the Korean peninsula was said to
be the first one ever recorded in history.
</P>
<P>
The adventurers set off from Zhujiajian Island off the coast of
east China's Zhejiang Province on June 15. The straight distance
to Inchon is 1,500 kilometers. At one point they lost contact with
their headquarters for 12 days because of radio failure.
</P>
<P>
They were varifying the theorty that people used bamboo or
wooden rafts to navigate between China and the Korean peninsula
more than 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"The success is hard evidence that Chinese and Koreans may have
contacted each other by sea as long as 3,000 years ago," said
Prof. Jin Jianren, a researcher at the institute.
</P>
<P>
Four ROK adventurers started a similar voyage from Zhujiajian
Island on July 22 last year. But typhoons forced them to call off
the attempt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
