<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Greco-Turkish Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has welcomed an agreement
between Greece and Turkey to promote better relations and believed
it could facilitate in a positive manner the on-going peace effort
to find a solution to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"The government welcomes the Greco-Turkish agreement to promote
friendly ties based upon the principles of international law and
the respect for each other's sovereignty," Cypriot government
spokesman Manolis Christofides told Cypriot journalists in New
York today, according to Cyprus News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on how this understanding will affect the
direct talks between President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, beginning in the U.S. today, the
spokesman replied that "we hope the timing of this development
would influence the talks in a favorable way."
</P>
<P>
He said the Cypriot government had obtained a copy of the text
agreed between the two countries at a meeting Tuesday between
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos and his Turkish
counterpart Ismail Cem, on the sidelines of the NATO meeting in
Madrid, Spain.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome this development and believe it would have
beneficial results on the Cyprus issue, particularly at a time
when talks will begin," Christofides told the press.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that "let no one doubt Greece's support
for Cyprus in a dynamic manner in efforts to settle the Cyprus
problem."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Greece's position that a new Turkish
offensive against Cyprus would constitute casus belli still
stands.
</P>
<P>
"This position has not been annulled," he stressed, adding
that "it has not been abandoned."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, have been at odds over
this east Mediterranean strategic island.
</P>
<P>
Athens has warned Ankara that any further advance of the
Turkish troops toward the southern part of the island would mean
war between the two countries. 
</P>
