<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Industrial Sectors Maintain Stable Growth in January-June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China registered a steady
industrial growth during the first half of this year, with the
industrial sectors above township-level generating an added value
of 984.9 billion yuan, a year-on-year increase of 11.6 percent
when adjusted for inflation, according to the statistics report
released by the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) today.
</P>
<P>
In the January-June period, the state-owned sector turned out a
growth rate of 5.5 percent, and that of the collective and other
economic sectors stood at 12.5 percent and 15.1 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said that the country basically achieved a
balance between the development of light and heavy industrial
sectors, during the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
The light industry generated an added value of 411.9 billion
yuan, up 12.1 percent from the same period in last year; that of
heavy industry stood at 573 billion yuan, up 11.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the consumer industrial goods,
including color TVs, washing machines, refrigerators and household
air-conditioners, maintained a year-on-year increase margin
between 14.7 to 27 percent, while the production of bicycles,
sewing machines and electric fans saw a decline.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the country's efforts to readjust the structure of
the textile sector, the output of major textile products showed a
quicker increase than before.
</P>
<P>
In the heavy industry, the output of major raw materials
registered a steady increase, while the investment machinery
products showed a drop or slow increase in production.
</P>
<P>
The sales rate of industrial sectors hit 94.6 percent in the
first half of this year, up 0.7 percent from the same period in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said that China's industry had shown traces of a
comprehensive revival, with the enterprises generating 43.3
billion yuan in profits in the first five months this year, up
35.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned sector has made up for its losses since last
April, and turned out a combined profit of six billion yuan in
April and May.
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out, these auspicious signs are
only the first step towards a long-term revival, and a number of
state-owned enterprises are still suffering from heavy losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
