<HEADLINE>   Howard Defends Australia's Racial Tolerance Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard today defended the country's record for racial tolerance
following criticism of federal government's handling of aboriginal
affairs and anti-racist party protests across the country.
</P>
<P>
"If you look at the overall record, especially in the last
generation, we are a tolerant, open, harmonious society," the
prime minister said today during his visit to the Thursday Island
off Australia's Cape York Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that "we have blemishes. Of course we treated
the indigenous people of this country very badly in the past".
</P>
<P>
Howard went on to say that "we've welcomed people from the
four corners of the earth. We took more Indo-Chinese refugees per
capita than any other country in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a meticulously non-discriminatory immigration policy,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
However, about 500 protesters here yesterday called independent
MP Pauline Hanson racist while One Nation Party Canberra branch
were holding its formation meeting, and 1,200 anti-racist
activists gathered near Melbourne Monday night in a protest
against the move by the One Nation Party to set up a branch there.
</P>
<P>
More protests are expected as the One Nation Party has planned
to set up 300 branches across the country within the next six
months.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent attack against growing criticism from within and
outside Australia of government's treatment of aboriginal people
and over the Pauline Hanson race debate, the prime minister said
"I am fed up with the self-flagellation to which some in this
country believe we should subject ourselves".
</P>
<P>
"So far as I am concerned, I think I speak on behalf of
millions of Australians, I am fed up with the sense of
defensiveness and the self-flagellation that some want us to
submit ourselves to".
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser was quoted yesterday by
local media as warning Australia facing moral crisis over its
handling of aboriginal affairs.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 aboriginal children were forcibly removed from
their families during 1910-1970 and an official inquiry report
calls for government apology for the practices and financial
compensation for the victims.
</P>
<P>
Fraser also backed the report's description of the forced
removal as genocide, which was rejected by the prime minister on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also made a strong statement last night that
he will no longer accept what he describes as unreasonable,
ill-founded and uninformed criticism of Australia's record on
racial tolerance.
</P>
<P>
"One of the things that annoys me most about political debate
in Australia at the present time is the way in which so many
people who comment about Australia, are spreading this view that
in some way we are a narrow-minded, bigoted people," Howard
complained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
