<HEADLINE> Sydney To Host World Transplant Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- About 1,200 competitors from 40
countries who have benefited from a life-saving transplant
operation are going to compete in Sydney's world Transplant Games
this September.
</P>
<P>
Each of the athletes has had either a heart, lung, liver,
kidney, pancreas or bone marrow plant.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the biennial games will be in Australia
and the first time that organisers have involved the families of
organ donors.
</P>
<P>
Sports will range from tennis, golf and lawn bowls to swimming,
cycling and athletics, the Australian Associated Press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The games were initiated in Britain in 1978 as a means of
celebrating life after transplant surgery and recognising the
people who made it possible, donors and their families.
</P>
<P>
Athletes from 40 countries, including Vietnam, Iraq and Romania
for the first time, will compete in the week-long event.
</P>
<P>
Games Executive Director Mark Cocks, a former professional
tennis player who has had two kidney transplants, said the
competition helped raise awareness about organ donation.
</P>
<P>
The games will begin with a ceremony at the Sydney Opera House
on September 29 with events at various sites across the city, and
close on October 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
