<HEADLINE> Israeli Labor Party Leader Cleared off Accusations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli State Comptroller Miriam
Ben-Porat said today that she had decided not to investigate Labor
Party leader Ehud Barak in connection with a military training
accident in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Israel radio reported that the announcement
cleared the newly-elected opposition party boss off accusations
that he did not help soldiers wounded in the accident and that he
left the scene before the soldiers were evacuated to safety.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Porat said that there is a contradiction between what the
wounded soldiers said after the accident and what they said two
and half years later. She added that she has no legal tools to
determine which version is correct.
</P>
<P>
She told Knesset (parliament) State Control Committee this
morning that shortly after the accident the wounded soldiers told
military police investigators that their shipment had been speedy
and efficient, but only two years later some of them changed their
story and complained about the behavior of then chief of general
staff Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
The accident took place when a missile was launched by mistake
during a training course, killing five soldiers and wounded six
others.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi accused Ehud Barak of
running away from the scene, leaving the wounded behind.
</P>
<P>
However, Chief of the General Staff Lt. General Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak, who was Barak's deputy and also witnessed the
accident, refuted the charge, saying that any claims that Barak
abandoned the wounded were a lie.
</P>
<P>
Barak was elected chairman of the Labor Party June 3. The
general-turned-politician is widely regarded as the only one who
can beat Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in the next general
elections scheduled for the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
