<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1 More Month for Non-Jordanians to Get Work Permits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 9 (Xinhua) - Egyptian workers in Jordan now have
one more month to obtain work permits from the Jordanian
government before being evicted from the country, local English
newspaper Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was the third time that the Jordanian Ministry of Labor
extended deadline to give Egyptian workers more time to get valid
permits that allow them legal work here.
</P>
<P>
The extension of the mandate was in line with a decision made
by Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali during a meeting
this week of the Jordanian-Egyptian Higher Committee co-chaired by
Majali and his Egyptian counterpart Kamal el-Ganzouri in Cairo,
according to Minister of Labor Saleh Khasawneh.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian workers in Jordan were first given three months to
obtain work permits starting from the beginning of last March, and
then the mandate was extended for three weeks and now for another
month.
</P>
<P>
According to Khasawneh, a total of 90,000 Egyptian workers
have complied with the regulations and obtained work permits
since March, raising the total number of Egyptian workers holding
valid permits to 125,000.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister stressed, large numbers of non-Jordanian
workers, including Egyptians, are still working without valid
permits and it is hoped that they would benefit from the one month
extension in order to avoid being evicted from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Upon the expiry of the new mandate, Khasawneh said there can be
no excuse for any non-Jordanian workers to remain in the country
without a work permit and employers will have to bear the
responsibility for their violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
When the second extension was announced, the Ministry of
Labor affirmed that the government would strictly apply the law
and requested that non-Jordanian workers without valid work
permits leave the country and pay both requisite exit fees and
other fines which they might have incurred.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said there are at least 300,000 non-Jordanian
workers in Jordan and 90 percent of them are Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
About 30 percent of the Egyptian workers are employed in
agriculture and the rest in construction work, domestic service
and a number of other services shunned by Jordanian job seekers.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government started to limit the number of
foreign laborers in 1996 for fear that they might give rise to
unemployment among the Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Jordanian government issued an order to close 16
occupations to non-Jordanians. The Ministry of Labor only issued
42,976 work permits to non-Jordanian workers, a 55 percent
decrease from the figure of 94,333 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Also last year, the Jordanian government concluded an
agreement with the Egyptian government, which stipulated that
Egyptian workers in Jordan acquire work permits through the
Jordanian Embassy in Cairo before they were allowed entry to the
kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drilling Technology Expected To Boost China's Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bohai Oil Field in north China
has made great headway in oil and gas exploration by using fast
drilling technology.
</P>
<P>
Some nine S-shaped oil wells in the Bohai Sea have been sunk
using this technology, at an average depth of 2,464 meters.
</P>
<P>
According to a Bohai Oil Field official, it took only seven
days for each of these oil wells to be drilled, four times faster
than with the previously used technology. And the production cost
for each of the wells was cut 46 percent, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the fast drilling technology has been successful in
three oil and gas fields since it was put into trial practised in
August, 1995, saving a total of 70 million yuan and bringing 450
million yuan in profits.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, a total of 200 oil wells have been
drilled in the Bohai Oil Field in the past 30 years, where there
are more than 800 million tons of proven oil reserves and an
annual crude production capacity of two million tons.
</P>
<P>
The new drilling technology is expected to increase the
country's oil production in the coming years, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
