<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Summit of Eastward Expansion Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) concluded its two-day summit today in the
Spanish capital of Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government of 16 NATO members,
representatives of the Western European Union (WEU) and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), were
present at Tuesday's meeting. They were then joined on Wednesday
by NATO's 27 Partnership for Peace (PfP) countries.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the first day of the two-day summit, the Czech
Republic, Hungary and Poland were invited to begin accession talks
with NATO, marking the formal implementation of NATO's eastward
expansion plan, which came into being about three and a half years
ago.
</P>
<P>
As for other candidates, especially Romania and Slovenia, NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said, "We reaffirm that NATO
remains open to new members under Article 10 of the North Atlantic
Treaty."
</P>
<P>
"No European democratic country whose admission would fulfil
the objectives of the Treaty will be excluded from consideration,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
NATO aims to sign the protocol of accession with the three
countries at the time of NATO's ministerial meetings in
December. It is hoped that the three former Warsaw Pact countries
will become NATO's new members in April 1999, when NATO marks its
50th anniversary of the Washington Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, NATO leaders reaffirmed that the NATO-led
Stabilization Force (SFOR) will remain in Bosnia and Herzegovina
till next June. They called on the authorities in Bosnia and
Herzegovina to accelerate the implementation of the 1995 Bosnia
Peace Agreement.
</P>
<P>
"While SFOR's mandate comes to an end in June 1998, we have a
commitment to and a long-term interest in stability in Bosnia and
Herzegovina and the surrounding region," NATO heads of state and
government said in a special declaration issued after a luncheon.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders called on the parties to the Peace Agreement,
signed on December 14, 1995 in Paris after it had been negotiated
in Dayton, Ohio, "to comply fully with the commitments they
themselves have agreed and to implement the Peace Agreement
without delay".
</P>
<P>
The SFOR of 31,000 troops was activated on December 20, 1996,
when the one-year mandate of its predecessor, the Implementation
Force (IFOR), expired.
</P>
<P>
On the second and last day, NATO chief Solana, heads of state
and government of 16 NATO members, and Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma formally signed the "Charter for a Distinctive Partnership
Between NATO and Ukraine", initiated on May 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
A NATO-Ukraine Committee will be established
accordingly. Regular consultative meetings between the alliance
and Ukraine and the exchange of military liaison officers will be
arranged.
</P>
<P>
As the Founding Act on Mutual Relations, Cooperation and
Security Between NATO and Russian signed last May, the
NATO-Ukraine Charter comprises several parts, covering the major
principles, consultation and cooperation mechanisms to ensure
safety in Europe.
</P>
<P>
In the charter, NATO allies reaffirm their support for
Ukrainian sovereignty and independence, territorial integrity,
democratic development, economic prosperity and status as a
non-nuclear weapons state, as well as the principle of
inviolability of frontiers.
</P>
<P>
The Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council (EAPC), including NATO
members and PfPs, had its first meeting at the level of heads of
state and government on Wednesday before the end of the summit.
</P>
<P>
EAPC, set up on May 30, 1997, replaces the North Atlantic
Cooperation Council (NACC) established at the end of 1991. It
provides the overarching framework for political and
security-related consultations and for enhanced cooperation under
PfP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Groundwater Level Back Up in Eastern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The water table around the cities
of Suzhou, Wuxi, and Changzhou in the southern part of east
China's Jiangsu Province has risen one to three meters.
</P>
<P>
The speed of local ground subsidence has also shown some signs
of slowing down, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
The three cities, which are located in an economically-booming
areas, have spent nearly 80 million yuan (about nine million US
dollars) on 1,200 water-saving facilities that will recycle 60
percent of the water used for industry.
</P>
<P>
The groundwater use and the number of deep wells in the region
have decreased in recent years, and systems have been worked out
to save more subterranean water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
