<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Civil Servants Get Higher Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Macao's civil servants get a higher
pay from this month, up 6.38 percent on their previous level,
according to a bill passed by the Macao Legislative Assembly on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News reported today that after the increase of
wages, Macao governor's monthly salary will rise from 123,165 to
129,734 patacas (about 16,422 US dollars), and his secretaries' to
97,300.50 patacas (about 12,316 US dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the government has to increase expenditure of over
245 million patacas (about 31 million US dollars) a year. It has
to pay the civil service more than four billion patacas a year,
accounting for 35 percent of the government's budgeted
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly income of Macao residents is around 4,000
patacas (about 506 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News said in a commentary that it may become a
huge burden for the future Macao Special Administrative Region
(SAR) following successive pay rises in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
"The successive pay rises over the past decade has gone too
far," it said. "It paid no attention to Macao's social conditions
and a sluggish economy. It might mean a heavy burden for the
future SAR if it is not brought to a halt."
</P>
<P>
Macao's inflation rate for the first six months of the year
was only 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The tiny territory now has more than 18,600 civil servants,
comparing with 8,400 in 1987 when China and Portugal signed the
joint declaration on the question of Macao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fairly Strong Earthquake Rocks Tokyo Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A fairly strong earthquake
registering 5.0 on the Richter scale jolted Tokyo and its vicinity
today, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake, which occurred at 6:38 p.m. (0938
GMT), was about 80 kilometers underground in the northwestern part
of Chiba Prefecture, east of Tokyo, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said there were no fears of tidal waves.
</P>
<P>
Japan Railway officials said the tremor has not affected any
railway services.
</P>
<P>
However, the quake shook homes and offices in the capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
