<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nigeria's Economy Rated Low for Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite some macroeconomic
improvements, Nigeria's future economic outlook still appears
gloomy, according to different reports of the World bank and the
Nigerian Deposit Insurance Corporation (NDIC ).
</P>
<P>
The World Bank in its "world economic outlook" for May 1997,
which was available here Tuesday, said although the oil revenue
improved the near-term outlook for the country, the medium-term
prospects however "remain uncertain", according to the Vanguard
newpaper today.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that "some limited progress was made during
1996 to restore economic stability in nigeria, but inflation,
while easing, remained high."
</P>
<P>
Latest official statistics show the inflation rate in the
country stood at 21.4 percent at the end of April this year,
compared with 28 percent last December.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank considered it to be about 300 percent higher
than the globally accepted inflation rate of five percent.
</P>
<P>
In its own 1996 annual report, also available Tuesday, the
NDIC admitted that despite some favorable developments recorded
last year, "the economy was still characterized by high
unemployment, low effective demand, inadequate infrastructure and
external debt burden."
</P>
<P>
The corporation, which, together with the Central Bank of
Nigeria, oversees the country's financial industry.
</P>
<P>
The situation, the NDIC stated, had serious implications for
the banking sector as the depth of distress measured by the
amount required for recapilization and non-performing loans
worsened.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that as at last December, the recapitalization
requirement of the distressed banks amounted to 42.4 billion
Naira (about 499 million U.S.Dollars) compared with 34 billion
Naira (about 400 million dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
meanwhile, the ratio of non-performing loans to total loans of
the distressed banks stood at 80 percent as against 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
All this suggests further deterioration in the financial
condition of the banks, the corporation noted.
</P>
<P>
While the total assets of the distressed banks rose by 11.97
percent in the past year, their total loans, advances and leases
decreased by 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
This was recorded against the background that the number of
distressed banks declined from 51 in 1995 to 47 in 1996, as a
result of the government efforts to sanitize the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The 47 distressed banks, along with three other classified as
potentially distressed, are however technically insolvent, the
NDIC said.
</P>
<P>
The NDIC attributed the bank failure in the country mainly to
unprofessional practices and attitudes of bank directors,
managers and other employees, insider related abuses, and other
financial malpractices.
</P>
<P>
While praising the performance of the African economy in
general, the World Bank said Nigeria was among some other poor
African countries that have fallen behind not only in relative
but also in absolute terms.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, these countries are facing a general need to open
their economies, reform governments, establish financial markets
and maintain international and external finanical stability.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the World Bank has recently announced
a 20-percent cut of its budget on Nigeria and reduced the number
of its projects in the country from oer 20 to 12 because of what
it saw as unsatisfactory results.
</P>
<P>
Despite Nigeria's remarkable improvement in the past few years
in maintaining stability of exchange rate, reducing inflation and
opening up the economy by promulgating new investment decrees,
the World Bank insists that much can still be done to provide a
more favorable investment climate.
</P>
<P>
The bank is reportedly said it would not approve its budget
package for Nigeria unless Nigeria shows seriousness with its
democratization process, deregulate the economy, harmonize the
exchange rates and privatize key parastatals among others.
</P>
<P>
Such circumstances, in addition to sanctions by some western
nations and internal problems, are posing threat on the 5.5
percent economic growth targeted by the government for this year,
observers noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Accusation of Funding for S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria Tuesday denied the accuse by
the Sierra Leonean military government that it is funding a
pirate radio that is aimed at destabilizing Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Acting defense spokesman, Godwin Ugbo said in an interview
with This Day in Lagos that Nigeria is not aware of the station
in question, let alone funding it.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Abdul Sesay, spokesman of the ruling Armed
Forced Revolutionary Council of Sierra Leone accused Nigeria of
masterminding the radio station during an interview with BBC.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean spokesman said his government was aware of
the radio station through intelligence reports several weeks
before it fully came on air.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the radio station is located at the Lungi
International Airport near Freetown, which is under the control
of the Nigeria-led west African peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Sesay claimed that the accent of the presenter during the test
transmission of the station is purely that of a Nigerian.
</P>
<P>
He called it illegal and unfair that Nigeria set up a radio
station on the Sierra Leonean territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
