<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Outgoing International Phone Calls Total 1.6 Billion Minutes Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong people like to keep in
touch, judging from the number of phone calls they make to the
other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
During the year between April 1995 and March 1996, outgoing
international phone calls amounted to 1.6 billion minutes, or 268
minutes for every Hong Konger, the New Evening Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Incoming communications totaled 1.6 billion minutes too,
according to figures from the Hong Kong Trade Development Council
(HKTDC).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has Asia's highest per capita telephone density, with
70 telephones per 100 inhabitants in 1996, when there were 3.4
million exchange lines, or one for every two people.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong also has some 310,000 facsimile telephone lines
carrying the world's second-highest rate of fax penetration.
</P>
<P>
Export of telecommunications equipment generated one billion U.S.
dollars to Hong Kong's coffers in 1996 while Hong Kong's telephone
exports ranked second in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
