<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Heads Urge Peace Talks on Sudan, Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of six eastern and
northeastern African countries today urged all warring parties in
Sudan and Somalia to put down weapons and hold face-to-face peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government of Kenya, Sudan, Ethiopia,
Uganda, Djibouti and Eritrea made the appeal in a joint
communique issued at the end of a two-day summit meeting of the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD).
</P>
<P>
The leaders hailed the acceptance by the Sudanese government
of the Declaration of Principles, drafted by IGAD in 1994, as the
basis for discussions and negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Under the declaration, religious factor is recognized as an
important role in Sudan's development.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) leader John
Garang arrived here Monday before the summit. But he reportedly
rejected face-to-face talks on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, an official from the Sudanese delegation said the
peace talks will be held between the warring sides in Sudan "in
the near future."
</P>
<P>
SPLA has fought in southern Sudan since 1983 for greater
autonomy of the Christian south from the Moslem north and now is
allied with armed opposition groups in northern Sudan as battles
continued in the country.
</P>
<P>
"In order to break the impasse, talks must be resumed by all
parties in the conflict so that a lasting solution can be found,"
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi vowed in his opening speech on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The IGAD held two high-level meetings in 1994 on the crisis in
Sudan but the talks were deadlocked. Since then, all IGAD peace
initiatives have stalled.
</P>
<P>
On siutation in Somalia, the joint communique said that the
six leaders expressed satisfaction that "the siutation in
Somalia, the joint communique said athat the six leaders
expressed satisfaction that "the situation in northern Somalia
was relatively stable and urged cooperation among the factions in
order to create a united and peaceful Somalia."
</P>
<P>
IGAD, grouping Kenya, Somalia, Ethiopia,Eritrea, Sudan, Uganda
and Djibouti, was set up in 1986 for enhancing cooperation among
member states on anti-drought and economic development. Regional
political affairs have been on the agenda of IGAD meetings in the
recent few years.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's chair is vacant at the seven-member IGAD summit as
usual because it has not had a central government since 1991 when
clan leaders combined to oust former leader Mohamed Siad Barre
and then brought the Horn of African nation into a war-torn
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
