<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Epidemic Reaches Advanced Stage in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The human immunodeficiency virus
(HIV) epidemic has reached an advanced stage in India, with the
country's Maharashtra and Manipur states continuing to have the
highest rates of infection, Press Trust of India said today.
</P>
<P>
latest consolidated data from all the surveillance centers
under India's National AIDS Control Organization (NACO) indicates
that one in every ten persons from high-risk groups are infected
with the AIDS-causing HIV virus in Maharashtra and Manipur.
</P>
<P>
The overall AIDS situation is worsening, NACO warned in a
report.
</P>
<P>
As of May 1997, a total of 3.03 million samples from high risk
groups and clinically suspected cases of AIDS were screened in
various surveillance centers in India.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 56,409 were found to be HIV positive, which indicates
an HIV positively rate of 18.6 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3,551 cases were reported till May this year, but
this only represents a small fraction of the actual AIDS cases in
India, NACO said.
</P>
<P>
The data indicates that the infection is spreading
geographically and has percolated from high-risk groups to the
general population.
</P>
<P>
The HIV prevalence in highly-prevalent states such as
Maharashtra and Manipur shows that the epidemic is in advance
stage, NACO concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
