<HEADLINE> Flights Cancelled As BA Cabin Crew Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of British Airways
(BA) cabin crew launched their strike at 6.00 a.m. (0500
GMT) disrupting Heathrow and Gatwick flights.
</P>
<P>
BA has cancelled 135 of 196 Heathrow flights today and
nine out of 93 Gatwick departures.
</P>
<P>
Pickets are also at Glasgow airport this morning,
according to a report from the city.
</P>
<P>
The company said, passengers turning up at airports will
be put on other airlines or given a refund if no BA flight
is available.
</P>
<P>
BA cabin crew began the first of a series of three-day
strikes despite a warning from BA that strikers would lose
perks and face a lockout unless they promised to work
normally in the future.
</P>
<P>
The dispute arose over the airline's plans to save a
billion pounds by the year 2000 through major restructuring.
Negotiations to seek settlement broke down on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Transport and General Workers' Union, which
represents 9,000 cabin crew staff, said the airline had
suggested an independent arbiter could examine the union's
proposals for efficiency savings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
