<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Vulnerable To Gold Price Movements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar today closed
slightly higher against the US currency, but lost most of its
day's gains when the price of gold slipped this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed at 74.42 US cents, up from 74.22
yesterday, but lower than its open of 74.64 and down from its
overnight high in New York of 74.92.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was traded in a tight range today,
reaching a high of 74.70 US cents but during most of the day
staying around the 74.55 level, said ANZ Bank's head of foreign
exchange sales John Reedyk.
</P>
<P>
Reedyk linked the fall to Prime Minister John Howard's
statement this afternoon, defending the Reserve Bank of
Australia's decision to reduce its gold reserves by two thirds.
</P>
<P>
Howard said "the Reserve Bank took a sensible, prudent,
completely unexceptionable decision in the interests of Australia
and in the interests of all of us in deciding to sell gold".
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, gold bullion closed today at 316.00 US dollars per
ounce from 318.55 at noon and 318.25 at yesterday's finish.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rate, the Australian dollar closed at 83.94 from
83.93 against the yen and was at 1.3092 from 1.3016 against the
mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
