<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Ukraine Sign Charter to Develop Enhanced Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and Ukraine formally signed a NATO-Ukraine
relationship document here today to further develop their
partnership.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, Heads of State and
Government of 16 NATO members, and Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma put their names on the "Charter for a Distinctive
Partnership Between NATO and Ukraine", initiated on May 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
A NATO-Ukraine Committee will be established accordingly, and
regular consultative meetings between them and exchange of
military liaison officers will be arranged.
</P>
<P>
"This is further proof that the European continent is building
a new security structure based on cooperation," Kuchma said at the
signing ceremony today, the last day of the two-day NATO Summit.
</P>
<P>
Solana hailed the charter as "a visible symbol of a new Europe,
which is not the Europe of the past, not the Europe of divisions".
</P>
<P>
As the Founding Act on Mutual Relations, Cooperation and
Security Between NATO and the Russian Federation signed last May,
the charter comprises several parts, covering the major
principles, consultation and cooperation mechanisms to ensure
safety in Europe.
</P>
<P>
In it, NATO allies reaffirm their support for Ukrainian
sovereignty and independence, territorial integrity, democratic
development, economic prosperity and status as a non-nuclear
weapons state, as well as the principle of inviolability of
frontiers.
</P>
<P>
According to the charter, areas for consultation and
cooperation between NATO and Ukraine, in particular through joint
seminars, joint working groups, and other cooperative programs,
will cover a broad range of topics including civil
emergency planning and disaster preparedness; civil-military
relations, democratic control of the armed forces, and Ukrainian
defence reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Closes Slightly Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A slight rebound in the gold
sector propelled Australian stocks to a firmer close today.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index gained 16.9 points to close at 2696.1.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries had fallen 63.7 points in the previous three
trading sessions after the Reserve Bank of Australia announced
last Thursday it had sold out 167 tons of gold in the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lifted 3.07 percent or 36.3 points, to end the
day at 1229.9. It had lost about 16 percent since July 3.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed in Sydney at 316.00 US dollars an ounce
from 318.25 US dollars at yesterday's close.
</P>
<P>
"There was a small recovery in gold but there's still a bit of
nervousness," Minnett Securities dealer Richard Coppleson said.
</P>
<P>
He said, the outlook for the gold market was still dependent on
the gold bullion price.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index added 13.6 points to 1444.6 while the
all industrials gained 22.0 points to 4306.7.
</P>
<P>
The insurance index vaulted 137.7 points to 6292.0 and the bank
index increased 58.5 points to 4967.2.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 435.8 million shares worth 1.15
billion Australian dollars (862.5 million US dollars), with rises
beating falls 690 to 459.  
</P>
</TEXT>
