<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Welcome Manila-Declared Truce in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The separatist Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) said today that it welcomes the
government's declaration of a unilateral temporary truce in
Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
But the MILF will not declare their own version of cessation of
hostilities since their troops are maintaining a defensive
position in the conflict, said Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman
for political affairs.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome this development but we will not declare a
cease-fire because our guerrillas are always in the defensive
posture and only fire back when attacked," Jaafar added.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to an order from President Fidel Ramos to the
Armed Forces to suspend their operations in Mindanao, particularly
in Cotabato and Maguindanao provinces, to give the peace
negotiations a chance to resume.
</P>
<P>
Ramos earlier designated Governor Nur Misuari of the Autonomous
Region in Muslim Mindanao to mediate an end to the impasse after
the rebels called off the June 28-29 low-level peace talks in
protest of the military offensive against MILF camps.
</P>
<P>
Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the Sixth Infantry Division,
confirmed Tuesday that the division had declared a unilateral
suspension of military operations as an expression of support for
Misuari's peace mission with the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Detoyato said the 48-hour truce, which will last until 6
o'clock in the morning on Friday, can be extended if peace
prevails in the areas it covers.
</P>
<P>
Detoyato disclosed that the military will maintain a status quo
during the implementation of the temporary cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
But analysts here believe the peace process will remain stalled
for some time since the government only met just one of the four
conditions put forward by the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF earlier also demanded the pullout of government troops
from the "occupied areas," particularly Camp Raja Muda in Pikit
Town, Cotabato Province. The camp was formerly the MILF's second
largest headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Other conditions include the safe return of thousands of
evacuees to their respective places and no more "provocative
pronouncements and manufactured accusations" by the military
against the MILF, according to Jaafar.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and government troops have fought fierce battles
against each other in Mindanao during the past several weeks,
killing more than 150 people and forcing nearly 70,000 residents
to abandon their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
