<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand for Cambodia's Asean Admission in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai foreign minister Prachuab
Chaiyasarn has said his country prefers that Cambodia's admission
into the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (Asean) be
postponed to December, when Asean leaders will hold an informal
summit.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyasarn told a cabinet meeting on Tuesday that it was his
hope that after a few months there might be greater political
stability in Cambodia, where fighting has been on since last
Saturday between troops loyal to the two prime ministers, Norodom
Ranariddh and Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen has gained the upper hand and is in control of the
capital, while Ranariddh is now in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The Thai foreign ministry on Tuesday withdrew a proposal to the
cabinet requesting the cabinet to formally endorse the admission
of Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar to Asean later this month when
Asean's annual foreign ministers' meeting takes place in
Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
Asean foreign ministers are scheduled to hold an informal
emergency meeting in Kuala Lumpur on Thursday to review the
situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
At an informal meeting in late May, Asean foreign ministers
agreed to pursue an earlier decision by Asean leaders to admit all
three countries in late July, a move to fulfill the Asean
founders' aspirations to include all 10 nations in the region.
</P>
<P>
The regional grouping celebrates its 30th anniversary
this year.
</P>
<P>
However, fighting in Cambodia has made it necessary to
review Asean's stance as it has had an impact on peace and
stability in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Explores Fish Markets In Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is exploring fish markets
in the Middle East and the Far East following a ban from Europe
of the importation of Uganda's fish.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ugandan Export Promotion Council who
preferred anonymity said that Uganda has found new markets for
fish exports in the United Arab Emirates, Egypt, Saudi Arab and
Lebanon, local daily "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations on fish export have been made recently between
Uganda and those countries, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''We have been exporting to the Middle East,
specifically to the United Arab Emirates, which re-exports our
fish to other Arab countries."
</P>
<P>
Fish export industry in Uganda has grown at a tremendous rate
since it began fish export some seven and a half years ago. Now
the country has 13 fish processing factories with a total of
installed production capacity of 73,000 tons per year.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure from European countries, Uganda in
February this year suspended seven of the country's fish
processing factories from making further exports to th European
Union after Spain imposed the ban on importation of Ugandan
fish.
</P>
<P>
Other EU states also threatened to block importation of
Uganda's famous Nile Perch for they said the high level of
bacterial contamination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
