<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Economic Growth Slower than Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Israel's gross domestic product
(GDP) will grow by only 2.5 percent this year, compared with an
initial forecast of 4.1 percent, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
A report published this week by the Economics and State
Revenues Department of the Finance Ministry predicted that
Israel's GDP will reach 88.94 billion U.S. dollars this year
compared with 86.77 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country's GDP registered a 4.4 percent increase last year,
according to the report, which also forecast a 6.7 percent
unemployment rate, a zero-growth of per-capita private
consumption, and an 8 percent increase in industrial exports
(excluding diamonds) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the decline in economic growth to the
drop in immigration which means reduction in consumption of
durable goods and housing investment; declining investments; tight
fiscal and monetary policies and the deadlock of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations which have a strong impact
on Israel's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
It suggested maintaining the government's budget deficit
targets without raising tax burden and implementing tax and
capital market reforms as means to reverse the economic slowdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
