<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highland Malaria Kills 41 in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Forty-one people have died from
highland malaria in the past two days in Uasin Gishu District,
western Kenya, according to a Kenya Times report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily paper quoted John Kibosia, Medical Superintendent of
the Eldoret Moi National Teaching and Referral Hospital, as
saying Tuesday that more than 500 others are admitted in serious
condition in the district.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that 26 of 120 patients who had been admitted
in serious condition died at the hospital. "The situation in the
district seems to be worsening though medical personnel are
working tirelessly to curb the spread of the disease," He added.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Ministry of Health has taken swift action to
deliver enough drugs to the district, said Kibosia.
</P>
<P>
During his recent tour, James Mwanzia, Director of Medical
Services, said that there was an upsurge in mosquito density in
the western parts of Kenya due to heavy rains and his ministry
was making a headway in combating the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
A malaria outbreak was reported last month in Nandi, Trans
Nzoia and Uasin Gishu districts and the disease has now spread to
six more districts in Rift Valley Province.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Chebet, the provincial medical officer, was quoted as
saying Tuesday that the situation had been aggravated by
chloroquine-resistant strains.
</P>
<P>
A series of measures being taken to combat the disease
included the provision of 500 mosquito nets to each district in
the most affected areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government is also supplying special malaria drug kits to
all the affected districts and additional buffer stocks to Nakuru
and Eldoret regional depots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
