<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Crisis Has No Impact on Asean's Solidity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's internal conflict will
have no impact on Asean's solidity although the country will soon
join the grouping, an Indonesian legislator said.
</P>
<P>
"Cambodia's crisis is an internal affair. I think it will not
drag on provided it is not brought to Asean. Instead, Asean will
try to seek a solution to the conflict," Antara News Agency today
quoted Deputy Chairman of the Interparliamentary Cooperation Board
Zamhari Ar as saying.
</P>
<P>
Following the factional fighting between supporters of
Cambodia's first and second prime ministers, Cambodia's second
prime minister Hun Sen reportedly took control of Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement Tuesday, the chairman of the Asean
standing committee on behalf of Asean called for an immediate
ceasefire in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that Cambodia's internal conflict will not hinder its
admission into Asean," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asean is scheduled to admit Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar into its
membership late this month.
</P>
<P>
At present, Asean groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
