<HEADLINE> Central China Province To Continue Cooperation With HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one tenth of the fresh pork
on the Hong Kong market every day comes from central China's
Jiangxi Province, and its other poultry and fruit products are
welcomed by Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
The province, abundant in fish and rice, has become one of the
major suppliers of non-staple food to Hong Kong. It has also
become the biggest rice supplier in the country's coastal regions
after years of stable growth in grain production.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi officials are optimistic in the future of cooperation
between Hong Kong and Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has the market advantage and Jiangxi has the
resource advantage, so the two can complement each other," said
Jiangxi Governor Shu Shengyou.
</P>
<P>
Shu has asked leading officials of the provincial economic
departments to seize the opportunity to strengthen the economic
and trade cooperation with Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The province's current annual export trade volume to Hong Kong
is around 700 million US dollars, accounting for 40 percent of the
province's total, and experts believe there is still potential to
tap.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Hong Kong investors have more than 2,670
factories in the province with total investment exceeding two
billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China City To Develop Pillar Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, which used to be in
Sichuan province and was made a municipality directly under the
central government recently, plans to improve its industrial
structure by focusing on seven pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
These include the three existing ones -- machinery, chemicals,
and metallurgy -- and four new ones: electronic information,
building materials, tourism, and food processing.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has adopted a strategy of turning itself into an
economic center for the upper reaches of the Yangtze River and
Southwest China. Its GDP is expected to quadruple by 2010.
</P>
<P>
In the machine industry, it will make automobiles and
motorcycles the core; in the chemical industry, natural gas and
chemicals for medicine; and in the metallurgical industry, high
quality steel and aluminum, according to Mayor Pu Haiqing.
</P>
<P>
For some time, Chongqing has been a major automotive and
motorcycle producer. In 1996, it produced 120,000 automobiles and
over 1.8 million motorcycles. There are now 38 auto parts
manufacturers there, and over 100 suppliers of motorcycle parts.
</P>
<P>
Pu told Xinhua in a recent interview that the city will also
develop industries like electronic information, building
materials, and food-processing, and promote 50 famous local brands.
</P>
<P>
Lei Hengshun, an economist and professor at Chongqing
University, says that the new strategy is based on Chongqing's
particular situation and will help the economic development of
other parts of Southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors have shown great interest in Chongqing's
pillar industries. Over 600 foreign-funded enterprises have been
set up in Chongqing, more than 70 percent of which belong to the
chemical, metallurgical, and auto and motorcycle industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
