<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Death Toll Drops in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's national malaria death
toll has for the first time in a decade dropped by 60 percent as
a result of efforts made by the Ministry of Health and the Child
Welfare since it launched the Malaria Control Program last September.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement from the ministry, over 1,400 people
have died of malaria from about 500,000 cases reported
countrywide since the beginning of this year, compared to 3,000
people who died of the disease last year out of the 1.6 million
reported cases.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Stamps, Minister of Health and Child Welfare,
attributed the huge decline in malaria deaths to the ''massive''
malaria control programme launched last year.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the spraying program has been very
effective and the householders have been very receptive to it
because Icon, the chemical, not only controls malaria, but also
kills bugs and other pests.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
