<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military, Rebels Continue Clash in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Government troops and Muslim rebels
attacked each other with artillery fire this morning in Mindanao,
the southern Philippines, despite a unilateral truce announced by
the military on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the Sixth Infantry Division, said
the 90-minute exchange of gunfire took place just shortly before
the unilateral truce started to take effect at 6 o'clock this
morning.
</P>
<P>
To save the imperiled peace process in the southern
Philippines, President Fidel Ramos Tuesday ordered the military to
declare a unilateral suspension of military operations against the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in Mindanao for 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Detoyato said armed men identified as MILF members first
pounded the position of the 39th Infantry Battalion in Buldon
Town, Maguindanao Province, with several mortar shells.
</P>
<P>
The government troops, though conscious of the temporary
cease-fire, were then forced to retaliate and fired their mortars
toward MILF positions, Detoyato said.
</P>
<P>
No casualties were reported on both sides in the latest clash.
</P>
<P>
But Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military affairs,
insisted that the clash was provoked by the military who he said
fired the first shot.
</P>
<P>
"The military fired several rounds of 81 mm mortar shells to
MILF positions prompting our men to fire back," Murad stressed,
adding that government troops pounded "MILF-controlled areas" with
shells until 6:30 this morning.
</P>
<P>
Murad accused the government of sabotaging its own cease-fire
to justify a total war against the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which began peace talks with Manila in January,
pulled out of the talks late last month after the military overran
its second largest camp in Cotabato Province.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been raging between the MILF and government troops
during the past several weeks in central Mindanao, killing more
than 150 rebels, government soldiers and civilians and displacing
tens of thousands of villagers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
