<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Speed up Agriculture in Yellow River Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China plans to open up about 666,000
ha of land in the Yellow River Delta area by the end of the
century or in the early 21st century to raise the current
production level to two billion kg of grain and 75 million kg of
cotton, as well as 500,000 tons of meat and eggs.
</P>
<P>
Dongying, a major city in the area in east China's Shandong
Province, cultivated nearly 100,000 ha of wasteland and improved
60,000 ha of medium- and low-yield farmland by the end of 1996 to
have an annual grain increase of 50 million kg.
</P>
<P>
The area covers more than 8,000 sq km, and another 2,000 ha is
added to it as a result of sea silting.
</P>
<P>
The city has spent 260 million yuan on building water
conservancy facilities so as to get 480 million cubic meters of
water storage capacity out of the Yellow River, irrigating more
than 200,000 ha of farmland and increasing the range of flood-free
area to 1,033 sq km.
</P>
<P>
The city has helped to set up more than 2,000 family farms on
the newly-developed land, producing grain, cotton, livestock
products, aquatic products, vegetables, and fruit trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Says It is Keen to Normalize Ties with Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sudan is keen to normalize
relations with Kuwait that were soured because Sudan sided with
Iraq during the Gulf Crisis six years ago, a visiting Sudanese
official has said.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa Othman Ismail, Sudanese State Minister at the Foreign
Ministry, said upon arrival here Tuesday night that Sudan
supported Kuwait's independence and territorial integrity and
rejected any attempt to interfere in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
This was Ismail's first visit to Kuwait since the Gulf War. He
said "we support and underscore the Kuwaiti right" to demand Iraq
to abide by U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
