<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Rises in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus rose
15.4 percent to 906.8 billion yen (8.03 billion US dollars) in May
over the same period of last year, the Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus surged for a second consecutive
month, following a strong 92.7 percent leap in April.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the increase was the April 1 consumption
tax hike from three percent to five percent, which chilled
domestic consumption, Kyodo News quoted a ministry official as
saying.
</P>
<P>
In May, Japan registered a surplus of 412.8 billion yen (3.65
billion dollars) in goods and services trading, compared with a
deficit of 104.1 billion yen (921 million dollars) a year earlier,
the ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in merchandise trade increased 118.6 percent to
927.9 billion yen (8.21 billion dollars), following a 90.9 percent
surge in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Exports expanded 20.2 percent to 3,984.9 billion yen (35.26
billion dollars), while imports rose 5.8 percent to 3,057 billion
yen (27.05 billion dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
However, Japan posted a deficit of 515.1 billion yen (4.56
billion dollars) in services including tourism, down from a
deficit of 528.7 billion yen (4.68 billion dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Local economists predicted that the rising trend in Japan's
current account surplus is likely to continue for a period of
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
