<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Becoming Less Concerned About Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese people, who have been
quite sensitive to price fluctuations in the past, are becoming
less concerned about price and the number of lawsuits involving
pricing is decreasing, as people shift their attention to product
quality instead.
</P>
<P>
The price index is still published regularly in most major
newspapers however.
</P>
<P>
The Consumers' Committee in central China's Hunan Province
received 1,113 price complaints during the first half of this
year, accounting for only nine percent of the total number of
cases it handled, fewer than in the past.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, there were 9,113 complaints about
quality to the committee, accounting for 70 percent of the
total. More than a third of them involved electric machines or
appliances for the home.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the change to the country's macro-economic
controls in the past few years and to improved living
standards. People no longer seem afraid of the shortage of goods
that plagued China for a long time in the past.
</P>
<P>
Economists pointed out that one explanation for the change
might simply be that ordinary people know little about the market
and prices, and some people just don't bother to file lawsuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
