<HEADLINE> Demand for Dollar Pushes Baht Value Further Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Strong domestic demand for US
dollar prompted the baht to further fall in the local spot market
to its lowest level since July 2, when the baht was floated.
</P>
<P>
In the local market, the dollar/baht trading was quoted on
Tuesday at 29.15 and 29.20 baht, compared with 28.93 baht at the
close of trading on Monday, and around 27.50 baht at the close of
the first day of trading when the baht was floated.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the central bank set its reference rate at 28.922
baht, up from 28.578 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The reference rate given by the central bank is used by
commercial banks as a guide for their money transactions.
</P>
<P>
Dealers say that the baht's weakness was attributed to
commercial demand for the dollar. Thai businesses want to buy
dollar amid the uncertain direction of the baht under the float
system.
</P>
<P>
The floating of the baht creates a heavy burden for Thai
businesses which have borrowed foreign capital, as their debts
will add correspondingly to a decline in the baht's value.
</P>
<P>
Since July 2, the baht has dropped sharply, by 12 percent of
its value on June 30, the last day the country's fixed exchange
rate regime was in effect.
</P>
<P>
A dealer from Bangkok Bank said that some Thai businesses were
selling baht for dollars in order to pay for their imported goods
and pay off their foreign debts as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
