<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Police Hound Tamil Rebel Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan police are hounding
Tamil rebel suspects in and around Colombo on the orders of
Inspector General of Police W.B. Rajaguru, according to police
sources today.
</P>
<P>
This follows intelligence reports that during the "Black July",
the rebels would be engaging in acts of terrorism to cause death
and destruction in Colombo and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Rajaguru has alerted all police stations in the city to be
extra vigilant to the rebel plans and ordered them to round up and
detain all rebel suspects pending court action, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The police and the armed forces have tightened security in
Colombo since July 1 in a bid to prevent possible Tamil suicide
squad attacks during the "Black July".
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels mark "Black July" annually, the anniversary of
the 1983 racial riots.
</P>
<P>
Tamil rebels who have been fighting for a separate state, are
facing a severe setback as a result of the Jaya Sikuru (Certain
Victory) operation by government troops in the north of the
country and are therefore believed to be planning destructive
actions in other places in the country. 
</P>
