<HEADLINE> Milosevic Urges Bosnian Serbs to Avert Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia's Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic today urged Bosnian Serb leaders Momcilo
Krajisnic and Biljana Plavsic to come here for talks to cope with
their crisis, which threatens the Bosnian peace.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian president, who is very much concerned over the
crisis among Bosnian Serb leaders, said that the crisis must be
averted through cooperation and agreement rather than escalated
conflicts, which is in the interest of the Republic of Srpska and
its citizens.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic is expected to meet the two Bosnian Serb leaders to
discuss measures to avert the crisis and to ensure the progress of
the Dayton Peace Accord signed in December 1995, said Tanjug news
agency today.
</P>
<P>
On July 3, Robe Rt. Gelbard, U.S. assistant secretary, asked
Milosevic to help resolve the crisis with his influence and
prestige when he met the Serbian president.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic, president of the Republic of Srpska, and Krajisnic,
member of the three-man presidency of the Republic of Bosnia, have
been locked in a power struggle for nearly 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic disbanded the parliament last week and called for new
elections in September. But Krajisnic and his supporters dismissed
her decision and held a session of assembly, rewriting laws to
enable her recall and to strip her of defense powers.
</P>
<P>
Adrian Vilksinson, deputy spokesman of the United Nations
peacekeeping troops stationed in the southwestern part of Bonsia,
said today that the troops are closely monitoring the situation
in the Republic of Srpska.
</P>
<P>
However, Vilksinson said the peacekeeping troops are not on
high alert as the situation in the region remains under control.
</P>
<P>
He said that the troops still maintain cooperation with the
military representatives of the Bosnian Serb army, denying the
rumor that U.N. peacekeeping soldiers are guarding Plavsic's
residence. 
</P>
