<HEADLINE> Thai Finance Minister Upbeat About Growth Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Thanong
Bidaya insists that the economy is on the upside following the
floating of the baht on July 2, with improvements expected in
growth, inflation and exports.
</P>
<P>
Inflation for 1997 should reach 6-7 percent, far below the
double digits predicted by some economists following the rapid
depreciation of the baht, the Bangkok Post today quotes Thanong
Bidaya as saying.
</P>
<P>
The baht on Tuesday weakened to 29.20 against the US dollar, a
record low for the baht onshore, traders say. Before the floating,
the Thai central bank's mid-rate to the dollar was 25.75 on June
30.
</P>
<P>
Thanong said the baht should have been floated at least six or
seven months earlier. Because foreign investors saw the baht as
overvalued, investment slowed, causing liquidity in the local
market to tighten and increasing pessimism about the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said although overseas borrowing costs have increased with
the float, liquidity should increase in the local market as
capital returned, resulting in a better economic situation than
before the changes.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand recently increased its inflation forecast
from 4.5 percent to 6 percent. With a possible 10-15 percent
depreciation in the value of the baht, import prices for oil and
energy, raw materials and intermediate goods will rise, pushing up
domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry has asked producers to refrain from
boosting prices of consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
On Monday central bank governor Rerngchai Marakanond said the
authorities viewed the baht trading at 28.5 to the dollar as
appropriate, but did not say whether authorities would intervene
to support this level.
</P>
<P>
Some private analysts have said the baht could weaken further
in the next several months, possibly breaking the
psychological-important 30-baht barrier, although this would hinge
on how fast the authorities would move to lower domestic interest
rates to ease the debt burden on the private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
