<HEADLINE> Thailand Plans to Borrow 10 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand plans to borrow 10 billion
US dollars in the next six months to spur its economy and bail out
its finance industry, according to an aide to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented step would increase the government's debt by
a third.
</P>
<P>
The government is now negotiating to borrow 5 billion dollars
from foreign banks, according to Poosana Premanoch, deputy
secretary-general of Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh.
</P>
<P>
The loans might be available early next month, he said,
declining to name the banks that would provide them.
</P>
<P>
Another 5 billion dollars would be raised by selling
international bonds.
</P>
<P>
He said it was not that the government has a liquidity problem,
but that the government wants to keep a credit line available that
can be used when needed.
</P>
<P>
He also promised that the money set to be raised would not be
spent on government projects.
</P>
<P>
The decision to borrow the money was made after discussions
between Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya and the Bank of Thailand
last week, according to Poosana.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that money was needed to boost the country's
foreign exchange reserves. So far this year, the central bank has
spent about 6 billion dollars to rescue the baht when it was
heavily attacked overseas by speculators. The country's foreign
reserves now stand at about 33 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that the increase in debt is almost certain to
lead to another downgrading of Thailand's credit rating.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
