<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Charter Change Drives Die Hard in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Are charter change drives really
dead in the Philippines after charter change advocates were given
their third heavy blow by the Commission on Election on Tuesday?
</P>
<P>
Political analysts doubted that conclusion. They said with
almost a year to go before the presidential election, it was
unsafe to say that charter change groups have been killed in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
After an unexpected caucus on Tuesday, the seven-member
Commission on Election voted unanimously against a petition filed
by a leading pro-charter change group called the People's
Initiative for Reform, Modernization and Action (PIRMA).
</P>
<P>
This was the third defeat suffered by the PIRMA. Earlier, the
Supreme Court has twice ruled against the group's effort to call
for a plebiscite on constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
The country's constitution, which was rewritten in 1987 in
order to avoid a dictator like Ferdinand Marcos, set a six-year
single term for the president. However, President Fidel Ramos'
supporters, including the PIRMA members, have been trying to lift
the term limits for Ramos and other incumbent officials and
lawmakers by changing the charter.
</P>
<P>
The commission's decision was widely welcomed by the opposition
and other walks of life. However, their joy may be short-lived.
Analysts said what had happened in the country proved that the
PIRMA died hard.
</P>
<P>
PIRMA executive director Mike Policarpio said he was very sad
about the commission's decision, but he would not give up. He said
his group would go back to the Supreme Court and find an issue
that would not be rejected outright by the court.
</P>
<P>
Legal sources had earlier raised the possibility that in
another round at the Supreme Court, the PIRMA may change the
fragile equation of voting in the court and win.
</P>
<P>
The Court voted 6-6 with an absentee on June 10 to uphold its
early ban on moves to amend the constitution. Legal sources said
that three judges who participated in the voting are retiring
after August, raising a hope of victory for the PIRMA.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Budget Secretary Salvador Enriquez, who revealed to
the public that President Ramos was "too shy to say" he favored a
second term, said "other options" are still open to the
pro-charter change groups.
</P>
<P>
The constitution can be amended through three ways in the
country: a people's initiative, the convening of Congress into a
constituent assembly or the calling for a constitutional
convention.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported earlier that House Representatives loyal
to President Ramos were considering the second way after the
Supreme Court banned the PIRMA.
</P>
<P>
However, House Speaker Jose de Venecia, a presidential aspirant
who enjoyed strong support in the House, opposed to changing the
charter before the 1998 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Some political analysts said that the "to be or not to be" of
the charter change groups was actually controlled by President
Ramos, who strongly opposed to charter changes but changed tune
this year.
</P>
<P>
In his recent report to the nation, the president called again
for review of the 1987 constitution to keep the country's fast
economic growth on track, saying that it was the people's right to
change the charter.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos has repeated on countless occasions that he
would step down as his term ends next June. But recently, he
admitted that it was hard to say "no" to supporters who favor his
staying in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
