<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vast Oil Bearing Stratum Discovered in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Oil exploration in northwest China
indicates that the vast Jurassic stratum there is rich in oil,
with an expected reserve of 13 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, the Jurassic stratum, formed from 180
million to 135 million years ago, was regarded as a non-oil
bearing structure by Chinese geologists.
</P>
<P>
But the China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) has
succeeded in oil exploration in similar strata, and oil
departments in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in northwest China
have discovered 23 oil and gas fields, including two large ones,
in several basins.
</P>
<P>
Oil exploration in Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and Qinghai
Province also indicated that the Jurassic stratum is an oil-rich
layer.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the CNPC, the company has chosen
five major oil areas in the Northwest and the Jurassic stratum
will be the focus of exploration in those areas in the coming
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
