<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Agree on Forming Political Commission: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Tha Afghan Taliban militia have
agreed on a proposal to form a political commission to decide
about ceasefire, exchange of prisoners and future government in
the country, local newspapers reported here today.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here Tuesday night by Pakistani Additional
Secretary in Foreign Office Iftikhar Murshad on his return from
Kandahar, Afghanistan, where he held talks with the Taliban
leadership, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The commission would meet in Islamabad, Murshad was quoted as
saying. But he did not give any exact date in this aspect.
</P>
<P>
Murshad termed his visit as highly successful, saying that it
was a step forward in the process to bring about negotiated
settlement of the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he would be carrying the decision made during
talks with the Taliban leadership in Kandahar to Mazar-e-Sharif in
the next few days for discussion with anti-Taliban alliance
leaders, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Murshad started the shuttle diplomacy two weeks ago. He paid
visits to Kandakhar and Mazar-e-Sharif from June 26 to July 1, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the reports also quoted the Afghan Islamic Press, a
private information service, as saying that the Taliban told
Murshad in Kandakhar they favored talks on condition that their
leaders taken prisoner by the alliance be released immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
