<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Mining Giant Looks For Manganese Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Australia's mining giant BHP Co.
Ltd is considering taking a major international partner into its
integrated manganese business to capitalize on forecast expansions
in the Asian steel market.
</P>
<P>
The partner is likely to be one of the major Japanese steel
makers or an existing ferro-alloy manufacturer supplying the steel
industry, the Australian Financial Review reported today.
</P>
<P>
Manganese, in the form of ferro-alloys smelted from the raw
manganese ore, is a vital ingredient in steel making.
</P>
<P>
The pressure to find a partner stems from dramatic changes
sweeping the manganese market in which ferro-alloy manufacturers
are becoming more directly aligned with the steel makers.
</P>
<P>
At present BHP's Groote Eylandt Mining Co produces about 2
million tons of manganese ore but only controls the smelting to
ferro-alloys of about half of that volume.
</P>
<P>
Graeme Hunt, general manager of BHP Manganese's Group, said
yesterday the company needed to increase that to about 80 percent
and lift production within the next few years to retain its market
share, particularly in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Our first priority is getting extra ferro-alloy into Japan,"
Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
About 95 percent of the world manganese production was consumed
as ferro-alloys in steel making, and with rising steel production
it was vital for BHP to conclude expansion plans or new alliance
deals within the next year, Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
BHP, or the Broken Hill Proprietary Co. Ltd, is the largest
mining company in Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
