<HEADLINE> Kyrgyz Foreign Policy to Serve Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyztan's new Foreign Minister,
Murafbek Imanaliyev, said today that the country's foreign policy
is to serve its economy.
</P>
<P>
A report from the capital, Bishkek, quoted Imanaliyev as saying
Kyrgyzstan will strengthen economic ties with the outside world
and absorb more foreign investment to boost the country's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Imanaliyev was holding his first news conference after being
appointed to the post on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign policy will not change with the personnel
changes in the foreign ministry and Kyrgyzstan will actively
develop relations with Russia, China, the United States and other
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the internal conflicts in Tajikistan and Afghanistan,
Imanaliyev said Kyrgyzstan would take an active part in the
mediating work, as the instability of the region would threaten
the security of Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
Following a proposal by Kyrgystan President Askar Akayev,
representatives from Russia, China, Pakistan, Tajikistan and the
Afghan anti-Taliban union are expected to hold an international
conference on the Afghan issue in Bishkek before the end of this
year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Before the appointment, Imanaliyev headed the presidential
administration's department of international affairs and served as
the country's foreign minister between 1991 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
President Akayev accepted the resignation of former minister,
Roza Otunbayeva, who was named the country's ambassador to Britain
and Northern Ireland, Interfax news agency reported on July 2. But
the report did not say why she stepped down from her post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
