<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Pakistan Call for Cooperation in Regional Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and visiting Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan
are calling for active interaction to solve regional issues,
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers announced this on Tuesday after holding talks
on the situation in Afghanistan, the progress of an inter-Tajik
settlement and the development of India-Pakistan relations.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that stabilization in Afghanistan can be achieved
only with the possibility of agreement by political forces and
then a coalition.
</P>
<P>
Gohar Ayub Khan, who arrived in Moscow on Monday for a two-day
visit, told Primakov that Pakistan recently initiated an increase
in inter-Afghan dialogue. This would be in preparation for
full-scale negotiations involving all warring sides of
Afghanistan, under United Nations supervision and in the presence
of Russia and the United States as country-guarantors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani minister is holding shuttle consultations with
Afghan sides to discuss preliminary conditions for a ceasefire
and the beginning of negotiations, but the sides are taking a
tough stances.
</P>
<P>
Both Russia and Pakistan noted that the unsettled territorial
problem for India and Pakistan in Kashmir is the only serious
threat of major military conflict in the world.
</P>
<P>
A conflict would have "dreadful consequences" because both
sides have powerful military potentials and advanced missile and
nuclear technologies, said Gohar Ayub Khan.
</P>
<P>
As for the issue of the eastward expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), Primakov said it would be
"the most serious mistake since the end of the World War Two --
although Russia and NATO have signed documents on bilateral
relations."
</P>
<P>
Primakov hoped NATO would respect and implement the agreement,
which "would actively keep the security of Russia and later change
the organization."
</P>
<P>
The NATO Secretary General, Javier Solona, announced on Tuesday
at the Madrid Summit that NATO had decided to formally invite the
Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland to join the alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
