<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Discovery About China's Symbolic "Flying Horse" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Dong Hong, a young archaeologist in
northwest China's Gansu Province, revealed recently that Zhang
Jiang, a Chinese artist of the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- A.D. 220)
had created many copies of the famous "bronze flying horse".
</P>
<P>
The "flying horse" was chosen as the symbol of Chinese tourism
earlier this year. It was first discovered in Han tomb No.1 two
years ago. The owner of the tomb was Zhang Jiang himself. Dong has
done a year of research on Han tomb No.2 since it was unearthed
near No.1 in March of last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that No.2 has a 38-m tomb passage and three coffin
chambers. On the passage walls are frescoes of moon and sun
worship in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Among the historical relics unearthed in the tomb are items of
pottery and ancient coins, and a bronze horse tail, which is
similar to the tail of the "flying horse", according to Dong.
</P>
<P>
Those buried in tomb No.2 were the ancestors of Zhang Jiang, a
senior official of the Han Dynasty, Dong said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
