<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Urged to Lure Foreign Investors With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government's review
of industry assistance is expected to recommend that Australia
appoint a high-level investment ambassador with authority to offer
foreign companies financial incentives to set up business in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The review will urge the federal government to adopt a more
aggressive and interventionist approach to attract offshore
investment, similar to that used in countries such as Japan and
Singapore, the Australian Financial Review reported today.
</P>
<P>
In another strong challenge to the Australian government's
economic orthodoxy, the government's information industries task
force, chaired by former Liberal Party President Professor Ashley
Goldsworthy, is set to recommend the use of tax incentives to
encourage multinational companies to set up manufacturing plants
in Australia.
</P>
<P>
A proposed overhaul of business assistance schemes include
reducing the plethora of programs to five core areas covering
exports, investment, innovation, competitiveness and
sustainability, setting growth targets in key areas such as
exports, providing direct financial assistance for foreign
companies, which could be used to purchase land or other
equipment, to encourage them to invest in Australia.
</P>
<P>
After a six-month inquiry, the review of industry assistance
has decided that the present system, which involves more than 130
programs and 1.5 billion US dollars in direct expenditure each
year, is cumbersome and lacks transparency.
</P>
<P>
The core findings of the report are now being tested with major
industry groups and within the government before it is presented
to Minister for Industry John Moore in about three weeks, the
newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
