<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Stock Market Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Weiguo, chief accountant of
the China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC), says that China
has been successful in expanding its securities market,
establishing a legal and supervisory framework, improving market
technology, and training securities personnel over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
"The sustained, rapid and sound development of the Chinese
economy has provided strong back-up for a growing stock market,"
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of the year, the Chinese stock market
grew 44 percent to 160 billion shares, on total capitalization of
1.667 trillion yuan, up 69 percent from the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 state enterprises have listed shares overseas,
raising nearly eight billion US dollars in overseas capital.
</P>
<P>
Market legislation has improved with a series of regulations
since 1993, on information disclosure, management of the stock
exchange, and issuing and trading stocks.
</P>
<P>
Zhang emphasized that the inclusion of securities crimes in the
new Criminal Law will help halt securities crimes by severely
penalizing those involved in stock price manipulation, insider
trading, giving of false information, and other securities
violations.
</P>
<P>
The use of better technology has helped build better operations
in the Shanghai and Shenzhen exchanges, with a high-speed system
of trading, information dissemination, and market surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Securities brokerages have also flourished because of the
booming stock market, with the number of people involved in the
sector well above a million.
</P>
<P>
"However, the most important and far-reaching significance of a
gradually maturing stock market lies in its role in fostering a
socialist market economy in China," Zhang noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
