<HEADLINE> Klein Announces Extension of Mandate in Eastern Slavonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Transitional
Administrator in Eastern Slavonia Jacques Klein said here today
that the U.N. mandate in the region would be extended to next year.
</P>
<P>
Klein, the outgoing U.N. administrator for the last rebel
Serb-held part of Croatia, made the announcement after meeting
with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Klein said "The mandate should be voted this week in the
U.N. Security Council, and my feeling is that it will be extended
to January 15 next year."
</P>
<P>
The postponement proposal was made among concerns that the
ethnic reconciliation has proceeded slower than hoped.
</P>
<P>
Both Serbia and Croatia agreed to put Eastern Slavonia under a
U.N. protectorate for up to two years and demilitarize it in a
deal worked out during the Dayton Peace Accord negotiations which
ended the near four-year war in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission has been overseeing the transition back to
Croation control, a move which, under the deal, must be completed
by January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the continuing demilitarization of
the region and the dual nationality of local residents.
</P>
<P>
Klein said that demilitarization was the main issue to be
solved by the peacekeepers and suggested that both Croatian and
Yugoslav troops remain at least 15 kilometers from the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
