<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Inspects Appraisal Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China has launched a national drive
to standardize its burgioning appraisal business by eliminating
unqualified agencies, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Administration of State Property
(Sasp) said a list of unqualified asset valuation agencies will be
announced soon after provincial branches of SASP wind up their
inspection of the 3,200 agencies under provincial supervision.
</P>
<P>
Sasp's headquarters in Beijing has finished the inspection of
the 107 agencies directly under its surveillance, revoking
licences for two agencies.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, when the first appraisal agency was approved, firms
have mushroomed throughout the country. Public intermediaries such
as accounting firms and legal offices also shared a piece of the
market.
</P>
<P>
So far, there are about 3,300 agencies doing valuation business
in China, employing 55,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of the business was brought about by
increasing property ownership and co-operation activities among
Chinese enterprises and overseas firms doing business here.
</P>
<P>
The current headache for Sasp, regulator of the appraisal
industry, is that many valuating agencies have been set up hastily
to meet market need. This has proved harmful for the industry's
healthy development.
</P>
<P>
Appraisal reports signed by these agencies -- usually with
unreliable and unprofessional staff -- often caused business
disputes or a drain on State assets.
</P>
<P>
Sasp believes the 3,300 agencies are definitely enough for
handling the country's appraisal business and in fact, there have
been more appraisal firms than needed in some areas.
</P>
<P>
With this in mind, the administration decided to stamp out
irregular practices and shut down bad agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
