<HEADLINE> Pakistan Launches New Peace Mission in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Pakistani diplomat who
is on a reconciliation mission to Afghanistan held talks yesterday
with leaders of the Afghan Taliban militia in Kandahar, the
Pakistan Television (PTV) said.
</P>
<P>
Additional Foreign Secretary Iftikhar Murshed is shuttling
between Kandahar, the Taliban's southern headquarters, and
Mazar-e-Sahrif, stronghold of the anti-Taliban alliance, in an
effort to bring Afghan leaders to the negotiating table to end
fighting in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Iftikhar held talks with the Taliban's acting Foreign Minister
Abdul Jaleel on the formation of a political commission which
would first take up the question of cease-fire and exchange of
prisoners between the government and General Abdul Malik, PTV
said.
</P>
<P>
It will be followed by drafting rules and regulations for
setting up a broad-based government in Afghanistan, PTV said.
</P>
<P>
Before departing for Kandahar Iftikhar Murshed said he has
proposed the idea of taking confidence-building measures between
the two sides, PTV said.
</P>
<P>
UN Special Envoy to Afghanistan Nobert Holl is also due in
Mazar-e-Sharif for talks with the leaders of the Northern Alliance
to promote a political solution of the Afghan problem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
