<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan oil exports rose to 10.5 billion
U.S. dollars during the first half of 1997, the state-owned
Petroleos de Venezuela (PDVSA) company announced lately.
</P>
<P>
The amount includes 2.172 billion dollars obtained via the
rights grants to 15 national and foreign consortiums and
companies, the company said.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The negotiations between Mexico and Nicaragua over
the signing of a free trade agreement have entered its final stage
and will be resumed in the next few days, declared Azucena
Castillo, Nicaragua's deputy minister of economy and development.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan exports to Mexico have climbed to about 14 million
dollars a year and its agricultural exports are the most
important. Its imports from Mexico totaled 43 million dollars, of
which petroleum and is derivatives are the main items.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Lincoln National Corporation, or LNC, the U.S.
financial services giant, announced that it will invest 85 million
dollars in Grupo Financiero Serfin (GFS), the third largest
financial group in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The LNC is considering purchasing 49 percent of Seguros Serfin
which belongs to GFS and could invest more than the 85 million
dollars "if certain objectives in the joint venture can be
achieved," the LNC president was quoted as saying by the local
press.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean wine exports reached 138.3 million dollars
during the first 5 months of this year, an increase of 48 percent
compared with the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the Association of Chilean Wine Exporters, foreign
sales of wine between January and May totaled 66,305,989 liters,
an increase of 15.67 percent over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The production of Brazilian petroleum will
have reached 2 million barrels per day (bpd) in the year 2005, a
would-be increase of more than 100 percent compared with that of
May 1997, Petrobras, Brazil's state-owned petroleum company,
announced lately.
</P>
<P>
Brazil produced 920,000 bpd in May versus 890,000 bpd last year.
</P>
<P>
To reached its production targets, Petrobras has already
decided that it will invest an average of 2 billion dollars per
year between 1998-2002 exclusively for oil and natural gas
exploration and production.
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Trade between Cuba and Central America increased 73
percent in 1996 compared with the previous year, the weekly
publication "Negocios en Cuba" (Businesses in Cuba) reported
lately.
</P>
<P>
According to the Cuban Export Promotion Center (CEPEC), its
most important exports to the Central American region are steel
rods and billets, medicine and twisted tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it also exports cigarettes, fowl, honey, coffee,
insecticides, lobsters and bottled rum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
