<HEADLINE> China Tightens Up Computer Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Public Security,
also safeguard of computer working environments, will beef up
efforts to fight computer viruses, according to today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
It will "supply more services for society" to effectively
protect computer applications, Yang Zhihui, director of the
ministry's Computer Management and Surveillance Department said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The services include a two-week upgrading of anti-virus
software and quick responses to individual pleas concerning new
viruses.
</P>
<P>
The State's computer security surveillance department is urging
its research and development organization, China Jinchen Security
Technology Industry and Commerce Corp, to take on this task.
</P>
<P>
As other efforts to protect the country's computer
applications, the corporation will boost the use of anti-virus
software by cutting prices and decoding the software.
</P>
<P>
It said yesterday it will lead other domestic companies to
decode its four new virus killers that will work on Windows 3.*,
Win 95 32-bit, Novell network servers and Windows NT networks.
</P>
<P>
It will also cut prices of its products by more than 60
percent, ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Decoding will cause economic losses for the company, said
Vice-Director Wang Tiejian. "But it is our pride to pioneer
decoding of software in the country" where copyright awareness
is not satisfactory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
