<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers are as follows:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Vice Premier Zhu Rongji urged yesterday at a national
conference in Beijing that people involved in the nation's grain
production must make concerted efforts to purchase grain at
appropriate prices in a bid to protect the farmers' enthusiasm for
production and maintain the sustained development of agriculture
and the entire national economy.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin expressed his belief yesterday
that the China visit by Malaysian Supreme Head of State Tunku
Ja'afar would promote mutual understanding and friendship, and
Sino-Malaysian cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
-- A conference held in Beijing yesterday said that government
officials and members of judicial organs who are involved in
corruption should be punished severely.
</P>
<P>
From January to May this year, 5,431 persons from Communist
Party or government organizations, administrative departments,
were reportedly involved in crimes of embezzlement, bribery or
misappropriation of public funds, according to the conference.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng hopes international friends can
contribute to enhancing understanding and promoting cooperation
among Asian-Pacific nations. Li made the remark during his meeting
in Beijing yesterday with overseas representatives participating
in the ongoing Transcultural Seminar on Economic Development and
International Exchanges in the Asia-Pacific Region Into the 21st
Century.
</P>
<P>
-- Qiao Shi, Chairman of China's National People's Congress
Standing Committee, said yesterday that China is willing to
cooperate more closely with Thailand and members of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations when meeting with a
delegation of the House of Representatives of Thailand led by
First Deputy Speaker Mophon Phetsawang.
</P>
<P>
-- A national conference on agriculture has urged all
departments in charge of agricultural production to spare no
efforts to ensure another good harvest of autumn grain.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Pubic Security Minister Tao Siju said yesterday that
the central government would clamp down on illegal entry to the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
-- China hopes warring factions in Cambodia will put national
interests first and prevent further deterioration of the
situation, Foreign Minister spokesman Tang Guoqiang said yesterday
in Beijing. 
</P>
