<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China City Protects Groundwater Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- East China's Suzhou City has
increased efforts to protect its groundwater resources and has
been successful in controlling ground subsidence.
</P>
<P>
The city has spent nearly 25 million yuan on groundwater
protection. Figures show that the volume of groundwater it has
used dropped to 60,000 cubic meters, which is within the range set
by the state.
</P>
<P>
The city's over-extraction of groundwater in the past has been
the cause of the surface subsidence, and it remains a hidden peril
in industrial and agricultural production and in people's lives.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the city has tightened controls on
groundwater use. There are quotas on water use at the beginning of
the year, and extra fees at the end of the year if the quotas are
exceeded.
</P>
<P>
The city has made stricter controls on the extraction of
groundwater, and has at the same time taken steps to increase the
recycling rate of industrial waste water to 75 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
