<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funding of Highways Explored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China is probing various
fund-raising channels to fuel a steady boom of highway and
waterway infrastructure construction, as the 21st century
approaches, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Besides continuing to use loans from international financing
organizations and foreign governments, the Chinese government
expects more private capital from overseas individuals, officials
with the Ministry of Communications said yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The country is planning to use the BOT (build, operate and
transfer) method, under which foreign investors run the completed
facility for a specified period before transferring it to the
Chinese, officials said.
</P>
<P>
As another means to raise funds, the government plans to list a
few expressways, including Shanghai-Nanjing, Shenyang-Dalian and
Jinan-Qingdao, on overseas stock markets, following the successful
listing of some highways of Guangdong province in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, China used about 5.8 billion US dollars in
loans from the World Bank, the Asian Development Bank, the
Overseas Economic Co-operation Fund of Japan and other foreign
governments to build ports and highways, said Vice-Minister of
Communications Hong Shanxiang.
</P>
<P>
The loans have helped build some major coastal ports with an
increased handling capacity of 85 million tons and 10,000
kilometers of highways throughout the country, said Hong.
</P>
<P>
In addition to using foreign funds, highway and waterway
transport departments are collecting fees and setting up
foundations for infrastructure construction, he said said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yingjia, deputy-director of the ministry's Highway
Management Department, said 110,000 kilometers of highways
including 6,500 kilometers of expressways, will be added in China
before the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to key highways across the
country: Tongjiang-Sanya, Lianyungang-Huo'erguosi,
Shanghai-Chengdu, Beijing-Zhuhai, Beijing-Shanghai,
Beijing-Shenyang and a highway stretching southeast from Chongqing
to the sea.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, the ministry plans to extend the
lengths of roads open to traffic to 1.25 million kilometers,
focusing on high-standard highways and expressways. China has 1.18
million kilometers of roads now.
</P>
<P>
Li Wuzhou, deputy-director of the ministry's Infrastructure
Construction Department, said the government plans to build some
major port hubs, focusing on those vital for energy transport,
foreign trade and raw materials transport.
</P>
<P>
Ports include Qinghuangdao, Dalian, Qingdao, Shanghai and
Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
Work to improve inland waterways along the Yangtze River, the
Pearl River and the Grand Canal as well as the navigation network
in Yangtze and the Pearl River deltas will also be the priority, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
