<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Craze Cooling Down for International Auto Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Only hundreds of Beijing people
toured the Beijing International Automobiles, Motorcycles and
Manufacturing Equipment Show (AMS '97), opened here Tuesday,
indicating the city's enthusiasm for auto shows is cooling down.
</P>
<P>
There used to be thousands of visitors to such auto shows held
in Beijing, and many of them were potential car buyers, according
to industrial analysts.
</P>
<P>
AMS '97 touted itself at the most authoritative auto show in
China, But due largely to the short interval between Shanghai's
auto show and the four-day event in Beijing, the exhibition drew
relatively few audience during the morning session, today's China
Daily quoted industrial analysts as saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 foreign and domestic auto-makers and parts
suppliers attended the event, most of whom now seem to have little
confidence in the compact of auto shows.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the potential car buyers to visit the
exhibition hope to see some cars immediately affordable, they
say.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that endeavors by all of us will revitalize the
industry and promote its strategic development," said Lu Fuyuan,
vice-minister of Machine-Building Industry at the exhibition's
opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has set a production goal of 1.3 million cars and
8 million motorcycles by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey of auto industry executives conducted by State
Statistics Bureau indicated that private demand for motor vehicles
would rise to 48.9 percent of all the vehicle sales, with 450,000
cars predicted to be sold.
</P>
<P>
Although beset by excessive competition, auto makers from
Japan, the Republic of Korea, Germany, France, Italy and United
States lost no chance to grab a bigger share of the most enormous
potential market in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
