<HEADLINE> Countdown Clock to Be Moved to Great Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- After drawing cheers and applause
from Chinese for 925 days in Tian'anmen Square, the electronic
timer that counted down the days, minutes and seconds to Hong
Kong's return will be moved to the Great Wall at Badaling.
</P>
<P>
Workers began to remove the clock at 9:00 pm yesterday, and a
model of the clock, one-156th the real timepiece's size, was
stored in the Chinese Revolutionary Museum, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A new clock to count the time before Macao's return to the
motherland will be set up in the same place on December 20, 1997,
two years before China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over
Macao.
</P>
<P>
"we have finished the design of circuits, and now we are
thinking of a different appearance of the new countdown clock,"
said Xi Guojin, deputy editor of Chinese Top Brands Magazine,
which is in charge of building the two countdown clocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
