<HEADLINE> Samaranch Hints Athens Has Historical Advantage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic Committee
President Juan Antonio Samaranch hinted on Tuesday that Athens may
have a historical advantage in its bid for the 2004 Olympic Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said the five cities bidding for the summer games
were "very precious" for him as IOC president, and "are in the
same status. But I would like also to say that maybe the Olympic
movement has a historical debt to Athens."
</P>
<P>
Four other cities seeking the 2004 Games are Buenos Aires, Cape
Town, Stockholm and Rome. The IOC will pick the winner on Senial
Gaesi
</P>
<P>
Samaranch made the statement while planting an olive tree from
Ancient Olympia in an Athens park dedicated to the Olympic
movement. IOC members who visit Athens each plant a tree in the
park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
