<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transnationals Pin High Hopes on Yangpu Development Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Many transnational corporations from
the United States, Japan and the Republic of Korea have shown
greater interest in involving themselves in heavy industrial
projects in the Yangpu Development Zone in Hainan Province, South
China.
</P>
<P>
The companies include the ACO Petroleum Co., Morgan Consortium,
South Korea's Hyundae Consortium, and Japan's Marubeni Corporation,
Nissho Iwai Co. and Fosuke Funai.
</P>
<P>
Yangpu, in the west of Hainan Island, is China's first
industrial zone solely developed by foreign investors and has
adopted one of the most favorable opening policies in the country.
</P>
<P>
After several years of infrastructure construction, Yangpu,
with an excellent harbor and rich local resources, has the
conditions to be built into a coastal heavy industrial base have
matured.
</P>
<P>
A chemical fertilizer project with an investment of 15.5
billion yuan from the China National Offshore Oil Corporation
(CNOOC), and a solely-foreign-funded pulp project have already
been approved.
</P>
<P>
Exploration by CNOOC and ACO shows that there are about 58
million cu m of natural gas in the Beibu Bay Basin, Yinggehai
Basin and Qiongdongnan Basin to the southwest of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
The annual handling capacity of Yangpu Harbor amounts to one
million tons. The second phase of an expansion project will double
its handling capacity over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 Chinese petrochemicals experts are drawing up a
development program giving priority to the petroleum and natural
gas industry.
</P>
<P>
The experts say that the development target for Yangpu has been
changed from that of a Hong Kong-style free trade and export
processing zone to a coastal heavy industrial zone like those in
Japan, the Republic of Korea and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Economists and entrepreneurs from the Overseas Enterprise
Association of Japan, who made an inspection tour to Yangpu
recently, agreed with this strategy.
</P>
<P>
The Nissho Iwai Corporation, Samsung and some other
corporations are consulting about iron and steel projects. More
than 20 projects in this field have already been approved, with a
total investment of about seven billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
