<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Ministers Agree to Limit State Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- European countries agreed in principle
today not to impose new taxes or regulations on business conducted
over the Internet and instead they will largely allow the private
sector to play a key role in determining how to run cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
In a non-binding declaration agreed after a two-day ministerial
meeting in Bonn, 29 European countries agreed that the potential
of the Internet could only be fully tapped if national governments
reduced their intervention to the minimum level.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said private investment and standards should be
given priority in building the Internet; no new tax levies should
be imposed on the commercial use of Internet; the right to free
expression should be protected; and data encryption technologies
should be allowed.
</P>
<P>
But it also stressed that international agreements were needed
to ensure that digital signatures on documents were legally
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by ministers from the European Union
(EU) and the European Free Trade Association nations as well as
some eastern European countries. Representatives from the United
States, Canada, Russia and Japan attended the meeting as
observers.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley said the Bonn declaration
was close to suggestions made by U.S. President Bill Clinton for
an Internet free trade zone, but there were also differences.
</P>
<P>
The United States requires providers of encryption, or
information scrambling, technologies to let the law enforcement
authorities have a "key" in order to gather evidence against
criminals. Washington also keeps a tight control on the export of
software with strong encryption.
</P>
<P>
Because a majority of software powerhouses are in the United
States, the Europeans fear that they will be put at a
disadvantageous position in this area and that it will enable U.S.
intelligence services to read their sensitive data.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the EU and the United States are scheduled to
meet in Brussels Wednesday to discuss the future of digital
commerce. The talks will focus on issues such as intellectual
property rights, the security of transactions, electronic payment
systems, data protection and taxation on the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
