<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Watches Closely Developments in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States is watching
the situation in Cambodia very closely and urging the two
political factions to reaffirm their support for the 1991 Paris
Peace Accords, the State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to review the situation as closely as we
can... (while) urging all the time the two major political
factions to reaffirm their support for the Paris Peace Accords of
1991, respect for the people elected in 1993 and respect for the
fact that we believe that any differences between the two factions
ought not to be resolved by gunfire," State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Troops loyal to Cambodia's Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen moved against those supporting First Prime Minister Prince
Norodom Ranariddh in the capital of Phnom Penh. Phnom Penh is
reported under the control of Hun Sen who declared to have ousted
Prince Ranariddh while he was in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said the Clinton administration is taking a
wait-and-see attitude with regard to the chaotic Cambodian
situation, which is said to be too murky at this point to draw any
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
Burns told reporters that First Prime Minister Prince Ranariddh
was to come to Washington and U.S. officials would meet him when
he arrives.
</P>
<P>
"Given our relationship with him (Prince Ranariddh), he's an
elected leader in Cambodia, we will obviously see him here at the
State Department," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Burns said U.S. Acting Secretary of State Tom Pickering
consulted with senior representatives of many countries Monday,
including ambassadors and senior representatives from the ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) countries, the other four
permanent countries of the U.N. Security Council, Japan and
Australia about the situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
State Department officials have also made telephone
conversations with Ken Quinn, U.S. ambassador to Cambodia, for
further information, Burns added.
</P>
<P>
Based on these meetings and the conversations, Burns said, the
Clinton administration reiterated its position on Cambodia:
</P>
<P>
The use of force to overturn the 1993 election in Cambodia is
unacceptable and the principles of the 1991 Paris Peace Accords
must be upheld; Cambodian political parties, including the
political party of First Prime Minister Prince Ranariddh, must be
allowed to operate freely; free and fair elections should be held
as scheduled in 1998; and the United States is opposed to having
senior Khmer Rouge leaders play any role in Cambodian politics.
</P>
<P>
The United States has yet to decide whether to evacuate its
citizens from Cambodia, but three ships carrying marines and
helicopters are put on alert in Japan in case an order comes
forward for evacuation.
</P>
<P>
The commander-in-chief of the Pacific Command in Hawaii has
ordered the three ships, the Belleau, the Fort McHenry and the
Dubuque, on alert "for their potential use (for) evacuating
non-combatants and maybe third country nationals" from Cambodia,
Pentagon spokeswoman Lt. Com. Karen Jeffries said at a briefing
today.
</P>
<P>
The three ships, carrying several hundred marines and
helicopters, are now based at Sasebo in Japan. It would take them
four days to reach the Cambodian coast if they receive the order
for evacuation.
</P>
<P>
But some other officials said the evacuation looked less likely
as the situation was actually easing after days of ferocious
fighting between rival factions in Phnom Penh, the capital of
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"The Pentagon is preparing for possible contingency if
something were to be necessary but so far the situation is
becoming more calm rather than less calm," they said.
</P>
<P>
"I think this is prudent preparation for a possible future need
but not something that's actually going on right now," they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
