<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Turkey Agree to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Turkey today agreed
upon a set of principles to improve their relations, including a
commitment to settle disputes by peaceful means, the U.S. State
Department announced.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a meeting between Greek Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos and his Turkish counterpart, Ismail
Cem, in Madrid. The meeting was hosted by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
are gathering in Madrid on the alliance's expansion and its
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The meeting among the three foreign ministers focused on the
Greek-Turkish dispute over the Aegean Sea that has burdened
relations since early 1996 when they almost came to blows over a
small Aegean island known to Greeks as Imia and to Turks as
Kardak.
</P>
<P>
The two sides committed to peace, security, and the continuing
development of good neighborly relations between the two, and
respect for each other's sovereignty, State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed their "willingness to avoid conflicts
arising from misunderstanding; and, finally, a commitment to
settle disputes by peaceful means, based on mutual consent and
without use of force or the threat of force," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe... that this is a significant step forward for both
Greece and Turkey," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe this is a new foundation for Greek-Turkish
relations, and we look now to both of those countries to take
practical steps to move that relation forward," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
