<DOCNO> XIE19970709.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Borrowing Up 2.9 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The increase of Americans' debt
burden slowed in May resulting mainly from the sharpest decline of
auto borrowing in nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) reported today that the consumer
debt outstanding rose at a 2.9 percent seasonally adjusted annual
rate to 1.21 trillion dollars in May, following increases at a 9.7
percent rate in April and a 2.7 percent rate in March,
</P>
<P>
The report said that credit-card debt inched higher at a 1.8
percent annual rate in May, down from 13.4 percent a month
earlier. Auto loans outstanding fell at a rate of 5.4 percent, the
largest decline since October 1992 and down from an advance at a
14.5 percent rate in April.
</P>
<P>
Other kinds of consumer debt rose at a 13.3 percent rate, after
shrinking at a 0.3 percent rate in April. This category includes
loans for mobile homes, education, boats and vacations. The report
doesn't include home mortgages or home equity loans.
</P>
<P>
It was another sign that the U.S. economic growth was
moderating after a strong increase in the first quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Consumer-spending represents about two-thirds of overall U.S.
economic activity. Its sharp increase early in the year prompted
the U.S. Fed to dampen demand by raising short-term interest rates
a quarter percentage point on March 25.
</P>
<P>
The moderation in the April-June period, when analysts believe
economic growth slowed to about a 2 percent rate, has allowed the
U.S. central bank to postpone further rate increases.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the report provided more evidence that
consumers took a breather after a spending spree early in the year
that powered first-quarter economic growth to a decade-high 5.9
percent annual rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
