<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy to Grow 3.1 Percent in 1997: Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada's economy is expected to grow
3.1 percent this year and 2.8 percent in 1998, an economic think
tank said here today.
</P>
<P>
In its summer outlook released today, the Conference Board of
Canada revised upwards its overall growth projections for this
year and the next.
</P>
<P>
Its previous projections set Canada's 1997 economic growth at
2.9 percent in 1997 and 2.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"This upturn in overall growth comes at a good time for
debt-laden consumers, since it reflects the recent surge in job
creation," said Paul Darby, director of economic services of the
board.
</P>
<P>
"Since mid-1996, production has been outpacing job creation and
with good prospects for further demand growth, employers are
starting to hire," he added.
</P>
<P>
The job creation of the last three months, low interest rates
and wage gains will provide a foundation for improved consumer
demand, the board said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, consumer recovery will be contained because savings have
dwindled to almost nothing, household debt is at record levels and
bankruptcies have been soaring, it noted.
</P>
<P>
While Canada's exports are to remain robust, export growth will
likely lag imports this year.
</P>
<P>
It forecast that the country's inflation will remain stable,
averaging 1.9 percent this year and 2.2 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Its unemployment rate will average 9.5 percent this year, down
from 9.7 percent last year, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
